WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.000 --> 00:01:15.570


2
00:01:15.570 --> 00:01:17.400
Old John of Gaunt,

3
00:01:17.400 --> 00:01:19.100
time-honored Lancaster,

4
00:01:20.200 --> 00:01:22.070
hast thou, according tothy oath and band,

5
00:01:22.070 --> 00:01:24.670
brought hither HenryHereford, thy bold son,

6
00:01:24.670 --> 00:01:27.130
here to make good theboisterous late appeal,

7
00:01:27.130 --> 00:01:28.970
which then our leisurewould not let us hear,

8
00:01:28.970 --> 00:01:31.700
against the duke ofNorfolk, Thomas Mowbray?

9
00:01:31.700 --> 00:01:32.870
I have, my liege.

10
00:01:32.870 --> 00:01:35.000
Tell me, moreover, hastthou sounded him

11
00:01:35.000 --> 00:01:37.570
if he appeal the duke onancient malice,

12
00:01:37.570 --> 00:01:40.100
or worthily, as a goodsubject should,

13
00:01:40.100 --> 00:01:43.030
on some known ground oftreachery in him?

14
00:01:43.030 --> 00:01:45.870
As near as I could sifthim on that argument,

15
00:01:45.870 --> 00:01:48.870
on some apparent dangerseen in him aimed atYour Highness.

16
00:01:48.870 --> 00:01:51.500
No inveterate malice.

17
00:01:51.500 --> 00:01:53.300
Then call them to ourpresence.

18
00:01:54.770 --> 00:01:58.100
Face to face and frowningbrow to brow,

19
00:01:58.100 --> 00:02:02.070
ourselves will hear theaccuser and the accusedfreely speak.

20
00:02:04.830 --> 00:02:07.670
High-stomached are theyboth and full of ire,

21
00:02:07.670 --> 00:02:11.770
in rage deaf as the sea,hasty as fire.

22
00:02:34.330 --> 00:02:37.900
Many years of happy daysbefall my gracious sovereign,

23
00:02:37.900 --> 00:02:40.300
my most loving liege.

24
00:02:40.300 --> 00:02:42.400
Each day still betterother's happiness

25
00:02:42.400 --> 00:02:44.470
until the heavens, envyingearth's good hap,

26
00:02:44.470 --> 00:02:46.570
add an immortal title toyour crown.

27
00:02:46.570 --> 00:02:48.400
We thank you both.

28
00:02:48.400 --> 00:02:51.830
Yet one but flatters us,as well appeareth by thecause you come,

29
00:02:51.830 --> 00:02:55.570
namely to appeal eachother of high treason.

30
00:02:55.570 --> 00:02:57.300
Cousin of Hereford, whatdost thou object

31
00:02:57.300 --> 00:02:59.400
against the duke ofNorfolk, Thomas Mowbray?

32
00:03:00.930 --> 00:03:04.200
First, heaven be therecord to my speech.

33
00:03:04.200 --> 00:03:06.770
In the devotion of asubject's love,

34
00:03:06.770 --> 00:03:09.200
tendering the precioussafety of my prince

35
00:03:09.200 --> 00:03:11.470
and free from othermisbegotten hate,

36
00:03:11.470 --> 00:03:14.230
come I appellant to thisprincely presence.

37
00:03:17.170 --> 00:03:19.630
Now, Thomas Mowbray, do Iturn to thee,

38
00:03:19.630 --> 00:03:22.170
and mark my greeting well,

39
00:03:22.170 --> 00:03:25.070
for what I speak my body shallmake good upon this earth

40
00:03:25.070 --> 00:03:28.730
or my divine soul answerit in heaven.

41
00:03:28.730 --> 00:03:31.830
Thou art a traitor and amiscreant,

42
00:03:31.830 --> 00:03:35.130
too good to be so and toobad to live,

43
00:03:35.130 --> 00:03:37.470
since the more fair andcrystal is the sky,

44
00:03:37.470 --> 00:03:41.030
the uglier seem the cloudsthat in it fly.

45
00:03:41.030 --> 00:03:43.170
Once more, the more toaggravate the note,

46
00:03:43.170 --> 00:03:46.170
with a foul traitor's namestuff I thy throat

47
00:03:46.170 --> 00:03:49.970
and wish, so please mysovereign, ere I move,

48
00:03:49.970 --> 00:03:53.370
what my tongue speaks myright drawn sword may prove.

49
00:03:55.070 --> 00:03:58.730
Let not my cold words hereaccuse my zeal.

50
00:03:58.730 --> 00:04:00.530
'Tis not the trial of awoman's war.

51
00:04:00.530 --> 00:04:02.130
The bitter clamor of twoeager tongues

52
00:04:02.130 --> 00:04:04.430
can arbitrate this causebetwixt us twain.

53
00:04:04.430 --> 00:04:07.230
The blood is hot that mustbe cooled for this,

54
00:04:08.400 --> 00:04:11.070
yet can I not of such tamepatience boast

55
00:04:11.070 --> 00:04:13.000
as to be hushed and naughtat all to say.

56
00:04:14.830 --> 00:04:17.670
First, the fair reverenceof Your Highness curbs me

57
00:04:17.670 --> 00:04:21.070
from giving reins andspurs to my free speech,

58
00:04:21.070 --> 00:04:22.970
which else would postuntil it had returned

59
00:04:22.970 --> 00:04:26.430
these terms of treasondoubled down his throat.

60
00:04:26.430 --> 00:04:28.430
Setting aside his highblood's royalty

61
00:04:28.430 --> 00:04:29.970
and let him be no kinsmanto my liege,

62
00:04:29.970 --> 00:04:32.130
I do defy him, and I spitat him,

63
00:04:32.130 --> 00:04:34.730
call him a slanderouscoward and a villain,

64
00:04:34.730 --> 00:04:37.470
which to maintain I wouldallow him odds and meet him

65
00:04:37.470 --> 00:04:41.200
were I tied to run afooteven to the frozen ridgesof the Alps

66
00:04:41.200 --> 00:04:42.970
or any other groundinhabitable,

67
00:04:42.970 --> 00:04:45.830
wherever Englishman durstset his foot.

68
00:04:45.830 --> 00:04:49.730
Meantime let this defendmy loyalty.

69
00:04:49.730 --> 00:04:52.770
By all my hopes, mostfalsely doth he lie.

70
00:04:53.900 --> 00:04:56.770
Pale, trembling coward,

71
00:04:56.770 --> 00:04:59.130
there I throw my gage,

72
00:04:59.130 --> 00:05:01.000
disclaiming here thekindred of the king,

73
00:05:01.000 --> 00:05:03.600
and lay aside my highblood's royalty,

74
00:05:03.600 --> 00:05:06.570
which fear, not reverence,makes thee to except.

75
00:05:08.000 --> 00:05:10.730
If guilty dread have leftthee so much strength

76
00:05:10.730 --> 00:05:12.530
as to take up minehonor's pawn,

77
00:05:12.530 --> 00:05:14.170
then stoop.

78
00:05:14.170 --> 00:05:16.870
By that and all the ritesof knighthood else

79
00:05:16.870 --> 00:05:18.400
will I make good againstthee,

80
00:05:18.400 --> 00:05:20.230
arm to arm, what I havespoke,

81
00:05:20.230 --> 00:05:22.470
or thou canst worsedevise.

82
00:05:27.970 --> 00:05:31.100
I take it up, and by thatsword

83
00:05:31.100 --> 00:05:34.500
I swear which gently laid myknighthood on my shoulder,

84
00:05:34.500 --> 00:05:36.600
I'll answer thee in anyfair degree

85
00:05:36.600 --> 00:05:39.230
or chivalrous design ofknightly trial.

86
00:05:39.230 --> 00:05:41.570
And when I mount, alivemay I not light

87
00:05:41.570 --> 00:05:44.230
if I be traitor orunjustly fight.

88
00:05:44.230 --> 00:05:47.930
What doth our cousin layto Mowbray's charge?

89
00:05:47.930 --> 00:05:50.700
It must be great that caninherit us so much

90
00:05:50.700 --> 00:05:53.330
as of a thought of ill inhim.

91
00:05:53.330 --> 00:05:54.330
Look what I speak.

92
00:05:54.330 --> 00:05:56.830
My life shall prove ittrue

93
00:05:56.830 --> 00:05:59.870
that Mowbray hath received8,000 nobles

94
00:05:59.870 --> 00:06:02.870
in name of lendings forYour Highness' soldiers,

95
00:06:02.870 --> 00:06:05.670
the which he hath detainedfor lewd employments

96
00:06:05.670 --> 00:06:09.100
like a false traitor andinjurious villain.

97
00:06:09.100 --> 00:06:13.230
Besides I say and will inbattle prove or here orelsewhere

98
00:06:13.230 --> 00:06:16.970
to the furthest verge thatever was surveyed byEnglish eye,

99
00:06:16.970 --> 00:06:20.000
that all the treasons forthese 18 years

100
00:06:20.000 --> 00:06:22.300
complotted and contrivedin this land

101
00:06:22.300 --> 00:06:27.600
fetch from false Mowbraytheir first head and spring.

102
00:06:27.600 --> 00:06:30.930
Further I say and furtherwill maintain

103
00:06:30.930 --> 00:06:34.070
upon his bad life to makeall this good,

104
00:06:34.070 --> 00:06:38.530
that he did plot the dukeof Gloucester's death,

105
00:06:38.530 --> 00:06:41.530
suggest his soon-believingadversaries,

106
00:06:41.530 --> 00:06:43.800
and consequently, like atraitor coward,

107
00:06:43.800 --> 00:06:47.170
sluiced out his innocentsoul with streams of blood,

108
00:06:47.170 --> 00:06:50.330
which blood, likesacrificing Abel's,

109
00:06:50.330 --> 00:06:53.100
cries even from the tonguelesscaverns of the earth

110
00:06:53.100 --> 00:06:56.900
to me for justice andrough chastisement.

111
00:06:56.900 --> 00:06:59.400
And, by the glorious worthof my descent,

112
00:06:59.400 --> 00:07:02.670
this arm shall do it orthis life be spent.

113
00:07:03.770 --> 00:07:07.470
How high a pitch hisresolution soars.

114
00:07:09.270 --> 00:07:11.330
Thomas of Norfolk, whatsay'st thou to this?

115
00:07:11.330 --> 00:07:14.000
Oh, let my sovereign turnaway his face

116
00:07:14.000 --> 00:07:15.970
and let his ears a littlewhile be deaf

117
00:07:15.970 --> 00:07:18.170
till I have told thisslander of his blood

118
00:07:18.170 --> 00:07:20.970
how God and good men hateso foul a liar.

119
00:07:20.970 --> 00:07:26.000
Mowbray, impartial are oureyes and ears

120
00:07:26.000 --> 00:07:29.430
were he my brother-- nay,my kingdom's heir.

121
00:07:29.430 --> 00:07:31.630
As he is but my father'sbrother's son,

122
00:07:31.630 --> 00:07:35.030
now, by my scepter's awe,I make a vow.

123
00:07:35.030 --> 00:07:37.570
Such neighbor nearness toour sacred blood

124
00:07:37.570 --> 00:07:39.070
should nothing privilegehim

125
00:07:39.070 --> 00:07:44.100
nor partialize theunstooping firmness of myupright soul.

126
00:07:44.100 --> 00:07:46.570
He is our subject,Mowbray.

127
00:07:46.570 --> 00:07:48.070
So art thou.

128
00:07:48.070 --> 00:07:51.070
Free speech and fearless Ito thee allow.

129
00:07:52.700 --> 00:07:56.130
Then, Bolingbroke, as lowas to thy heart,

130
00:07:56.130 --> 00:07:59.300
through the false passageof thy throat, thou liest.

131
00:08:02.000 --> 00:08:03.770
Three parts of thatreceipt I had for Calais

132
00:08:03.770 --> 00:08:06.570
disbursed I duly to HisHighness' soldiers.

133
00:08:06.570 --> 00:08:09.500
The other part reserved Iby consent,

134
00:08:09.500 --> 00:08:10.830
for that my sovereignliege

135
00:08:10.830 --> 00:08:13.170
was in my debt uponremainder of a dear account,

136
00:08:13.170 --> 00:08:16.800
since last I went toFrance to fetch his queen.

137
00:08:16.800 --> 00:08:18.700
Now swallow down that lie.

138
00:08:20.800 --> 00:08:25.270
For Gloucester's death, Islew him not,

139
00:08:27.370 --> 00:08:31.800
but to my own disgraceneglected my sworn duty inthat case.

140
00:08:33.730 --> 00:08:35.800
For you, my noble lord ofLancaster,

141
00:08:35.800 --> 00:08:38.300
the honorable father to myfoe,

142
00:08:38.300 --> 00:08:41.070
once did I lay an ambushfor your life,

143
00:08:41.070 --> 00:08:44.230
a trespass that doth vexmy grieved soul.

144
00:08:44.230 --> 00:08:47.030
But ere I last receivedthe sacrament, I didconfess it

145
00:08:47.030 --> 00:08:49.770
and exactly begged YourGrace's pardon,

146
00:08:49.770 --> 00:08:51.570
and I hope I had it.

147
00:08:54.130 --> 00:08:56.370
This is my fault.

148
00:08:56.370 --> 00:08:57.700
As for the rest appealed,

149
00:08:57.700 --> 00:08:59.830
it issues from the rancorof a villain,

150
00:08:59.830 --> 00:09:03.270
a recreant and mostdegenerate traitor,

151
00:09:03.270 --> 00:09:05.070
which in myself I boldlywill defend

152
00:09:05.070 --> 00:09:06.930
and interchangeably hurldown my gage

153
00:09:06.930 --> 00:09:08.870
upon this overweeningtraitor's foot

154
00:09:08.870 --> 00:09:10.770
to prove myself a loyalgentleman

155
00:09:10.770 --> 00:09:12.870
even in the best bloodchambered in his bosom.

156
00:09:14.130 --> 00:09:15.330
In haste whereof,

157
00:09:15.330 --> 00:09:16.900
most heartily I pray YourHighness

158
00:09:16.900 --> 00:09:18.500
to assign our trial day.

159
00:09:18.500 --> 00:09:21.470
Wrath-kindled gentlemen,be ruled by me.

160
00:09:21.470 --> 00:09:24.870
Let's purge this cholerwithout letting blood.

161
00:09:24.870 --> 00:09:27.070
This we prescribe, thoughno physician.

162
00:09:27.070 --> 00:09:30.170
Deep malice makes too deepincision.

163
00:09:30.170 --> 00:09:33.870
Forget, forgive, conclude,and be agreed.

164
00:09:33.870 --> 00:09:37.530
Our doctors say this is nomonth to bleed.

165
00:09:37.530 --> 00:09:39.300
Good Uncle, let this endwhere it begun.

166
00:09:39.300 --> 00:09:42.400
We'll calm the duke ofNorfolk, you your son.

167
00:09:42.400 --> 00:09:45.070
To be a make-peace shallbecome my age.

168
00:09:46.830 --> 00:09:49.430
Throw down, my son, theduke of Norfolk's gage.

169
00:09:49.430 --> 00:09:50.730
And, Norfolk, throwdown his.

170
00:09:50.730 --> 00:09:52.470
When, Harry, when?

171
00:09:52.470 --> 00:09:54.400
Obedience bids I shouldnot bid again.

172
00:09:54.400 --> 00:09:56.830
Norfolk, throw down, webid.

173
00:09:56.830 --> 00:09:58.370
There is no boot.

174
00:09:58.370 --> 00:10:01.300
Myself I throw, dreadsovereign, at thy foot.

175
00:10:01.300 --> 00:10:04.200
My life thou shaltcommand, but not my shame.

176
00:10:04.200 --> 00:10:05.570
The one my duty owes,

177
00:10:05.570 --> 00:10:06.630
but my fair name,

178
00:10:06.630 --> 00:10:08.730
despite of death thatlives upon my grave,

179
00:10:08.730 --> 00:10:12.600
to dark dishonor's usethou shalt not have.

180
00:10:12.600 --> 00:10:16.070
I am disgraced, impeached,and baffled here,

181
00:10:16.070 --> 00:10:19.570
pierced to the soul withslander's venomed spear,

182
00:10:19.570 --> 00:10:21.070
the which no balm can cure

183
00:10:21.070 --> 00:10:23.730
but his heart blood whichbreathed this poison.

184
00:10:23.730 --> 00:10:25.070
Rage must be withstood.

185
00:10:25.070 --> 00:10:27.270
Give me his gage.

186
00:10:27.270 --> 00:10:30.170
Lions make leopards tame.

187
00:10:30.170 --> 00:10:33.200
Yea, but not change hisspots.

188
00:10:33.200 --> 00:10:35.470
Take but my shame and Iresign my gage.

189
00:10:37.470 --> 00:10:39.870
My dear, dear lord,

190
00:10:39.870 --> 00:10:44.530
the purest treasure mortaltimes afford is spotlessreputation.

191
00:10:45.830 --> 00:10:51.030
That away, men are butgilded loam or painted clay.

192
00:10:51.030 --> 00:10:53.630
A jewel in a ten-timesbarred up chest

193
00:10:53.630 --> 00:10:56.470
is a bold spirit in aloyal breast.

194
00:10:56.470 --> 00:10:57.730
Mine honor is my life.

195
00:10:57.730 --> 00:10:58.900
Both grow in one.

196
00:10:58.900 --> 00:11:02.500
Take honor from me, and mylife is done.

197
00:11:02.500 --> 00:11:05.870
Then, dear my liege, minehonor let me try.

198
00:11:05.870 --> 00:11:10.170
In that I live, and forthat will I die.

199
00:11:12.700 --> 00:11:13.770
Cousin, throw up yourgage.

200
00:11:13.770 --> 00:11:15.430
Do you begin.

201
00:11:15.430 --> 00:11:20.730
Oh, God, defend my soulfrom such deep sin.

202
00:11:20.730 --> 00:11:24.200
Shall I seem crestfallenin my father's sight?

203
00:11:24.200 --> 00:11:27.400
Or with pale beggar fearimpeach my height

204
00:11:27.400 --> 00:11:30.000
before this outdareddastard?

205
00:11:33.170 --> 00:11:36.800
Ere my tongue shall wound myhonor with such feeble wrong

206
00:11:36.800 --> 00:11:39.030
or sound so base a parle,

207
00:11:39.030 --> 00:11:42.930
my teeth shall tear theslavish motive ofrecanting fear

208
00:11:42.930 --> 00:11:46.400
and spit it bleeding inhis high disgrace,

209
00:11:46.400 --> 00:11:50.270
where shame doth harbor,even in Mowbray's face.

210
00:11:53.500 --> 00:11:57.470
We were not born to suebut to command.

211
00:11:57.470 --> 00:12:00.400
Since which we cannot doto make you friends,

212
00:12:00.400 --> 00:12:03.000
be ready, as your livesshall answer it,

213
00:12:03.000 --> 00:12:05.770
at Coventry upon SaintLambert's day.

214
00:12:05.770 --> 00:12:08.030
There shall your swordsand lances arbitrate

215
00:12:08.030 --> 00:12:10.470
the swelling difference ofyour settled hate.

216
00:12:10.470 --> 00:12:12.600
Since we can not atoneyou,

217
00:12:12.600 --> 00:12:15.130
we shall see justice designthe victor's chivalry.

218
00:12:15.130 --> 00:12:19.400
Lord marshal, command ourofficers at arms.

219
00:12:19.400 --> 00:12:22.430
Be ready to direct thesehome alarms.

220
00:12:23.870 --> 00:12:26.170
Alas, the part I had inGloucester's blood

221
00:12:26.170 --> 00:12:28.200
doth more solicit me thanyour exclaims

222
00:12:28.200 --> 00:12:31.670
to stir against thebutchers of his life.

223
00:12:31.670 --> 00:12:33.300
But since correction lieth

224
00:12:33.300 --> 00:12:36.970
in those hands which madethe fault which we cannotcorrect,

225
00:12:36.970 --> 00:12:39.470
put we our quarrel to thewill of heaven,

226
00:12:39.470 --> 00:12:41.900
who, when they see thehours ripe on earth,

227
00:12:41.900 --> 00:12:44.900
will rain hot vengeance onoffenders' heads.

228
00:12:44.900 --> 00:12:47.930
Finds brotherhood in theeno sharper spur?

229
00:12:49.070 --> 00:12:51.730
Hath love in thy old bloodno living fire?

230
00:12:53.030 --> 00:12:55.300
Edward's seven sons,whereof thyself art one,

231
00:12:55.300 --> 00:12:58.030
were as seven vials of hissacred blood

232
00:12:58.030 --> 00:13:01.000
or seven fair branchesspringing from one root.

233
00:13:02.170 --> 00:13:04.600
Some of those seven aredried by nature's course,

234
00:13:04.600 --> 00:13:07.170
some of those branches bythe destinies cut.

235
00:13:08.830 --> 00:13:13.800
But Thomas, my dear lord,my life, my Gloucester,

236
00:13:15.270 --> 00:13:17.570
one vial full of Edward'ssacred blood,

237
00:13:17.570 --> 00:13:20.270
one flourishing branch ofhis most royal root,

238
00:13:20.270 --> 00:13:21.800
is cracked,

239
00:13:21.800 --> 00:13:26.030
and all the precious liquorspilt is hacked down

240
00:13:27.330 --> 00:13:29.000
and his summer leaves allfaded

241
00:13:29.000 --> 00:13:32.530
by envy's hand andmurder's bloody axe.

242
00:13:32.530 --> 00:13:33.900
Ah, Gaunt,

243
00:13:35.330 --> 00:13:36.800
his blood was thine.

244
00:13:38.370 --> 00:13:41.100
That bed, that womb, thatmetal, that self-mold

245
00:13:41.100 --> 00:13:43.270
that fashioned thee madehim a man.

246
00:13:44.930 --> 00:13:46.530
And though thou livest andbreathest,

247
00:13:46.530 --> 00:13:48.100
yet art thou slain in him.

248
00:13:49.630 --> 00:13:53.670
Thou dost consent in somelarge measure to thyfather's death

249
00:13:53.670 --> 00:13:56.170
in that thou seest thywretched brother die,

250
00:13:56.170 --> 00:13:58.270
who was the model of thyfather's life.

251
00:13:59.470 --> 00:14:02.230
Call it not patience,Gaunt.

252
00:14:02.230 --> 00:14:03.270
It is despair.

253
00:14:04.600 --> 00:14:07.470
In suffering thus thybrother to be slaughtered,

254
00:14:07.470 --> 00:14:09.970
thou showest the nakedpathway to thy life,

255
00:14:09.970 --> 00:14:12.570
teaching stern murder howto butcher thee.

256
00:14:14.100 --> 00:14:16.800
That which in mean men weentitle patience

257
00:14:16.800 --> 00:14:20.670
is pale cold cowardice innoble breasts.

258
00:14:22.170 --> 00:14:23.470
What shall I say?

259
00:14:25.070 --> 00:14:26.630
To safeguard thine ownlife,

260
00:14:26.630 --> 00:14:29.500
the best way is to vengemy Gloucester's death.

261
00:14:29.500 --> 00:14:31.130
God's is the quarrel,

262
00:14:31.130 --> 00:14:33.830
for God's substitute, hisdeputy anointed in Hissight,

263
00:14:33.830 --> 00:14:35.200
hath caused his death,

264
00:14:35.200 --> 00:14:38.270
the which if wrongfully,let heaven revenge,

265
00:14:38.270 --> 00:14:41.270
for I may never lift anangry arm against Hisminister.

266
00:14:41.270 --> 00:14:44.630
Where then, alas, may Icomplain myself?

267
00:14:44.630 --> 00:14:47.370
To God, the widow'schampion and defense.

268
00:14:48.400 --> 00:14:49.600
Why, then, I will.

269
00:14:51.570 --> 00:14:53.030
Farewell, old Gaunt.

270
00:14:55.000 --> 00:14:56.370
Thou goest to Coventry,

271
00:14:56.370 --> 00:15:00.070
there to behold ourcousin Hereford and fellMowbray fight.

272
00:15:01.830 --> 00:15:05.500
Oh, sit my husband'swrongs on Hereford's spear

273
00:15:05.500 --> 00:15:09.030
that they may enterbutcher Mowbray's breast.

274
00:15:09.030 --> 00:15:11.070
Or, if misfortune miss thefirst career,

275
00:15:11.070 --> 00:15:13.230
be Mowbray's sins so heavyin his bosom

276
00:15:13.230 --> 00:15:15.800
that they may break hisfoaming courser's back

277
00:15:15.800 --> 00:15:18.600
and throw the riderheadlong in the lists,

278
00:15:18.600 --> 00:15:23.300
a caitiff recreant to mycousin Hereford.

279
00:15:25.130 --> 00:15:26.670
Farewell, old Gaunt.

280
00:15:28.030 --> 00:15:30.470
Thy sometimes brother'swife

281
00:15:30.470 --> 00:15:33.530
with her companion griefmust end her life.

282
00:15:33.530 --> 00:15:34.870
Sister, farewell.

283
00:15:36.570 --> 00:15:37.800
I must to Coventry.

284
00:15:37.800 --> 00:15:40.830
As much good stay withthee as go with me.

285
00:15:40.830 --> 00:15:42.530
Yet one word more.

286
00:15:44.630 --> 00:15:47.200
Grief boundeth where itfalls

287
00:15:48.670 --> 00:15:51.430
not with the emptyhollowness but weight.

288
00:15:53.270 --> 00:15:55.270
I take my leave before Ihave begun,

289
00:15:56.170 --> 00:15:58.500
for sorrow ends not whenit seemeth done.

290
00:16:00.970 --> 00:16:03.370
Commend me to thy brother,Edmund York.

291
00:16:05.470 --> 00:16:06.530
Lo, this is all.

292
00:16:08.270 --> 00:16:09.730
Nay, yet depart not so.

293
00:16:11.670 --> 00:16:13.770
Though this be all, do notso quickly go.

294
00:16:13.770 --> 00:16:14.870
I shall remember more.

295
00:16:14.870 --> 00:16:15.970
Bid him--

296
00:16:15.970 --> 00:16:18.700
ah, what?

297
00:16:22.470 --> 00:16:25.470
With all good speed atPlashy visit me.

298
00:16:27.300 --> 00:16:30.000
Alack, and what shall goodold York there see

299
00:16:31.130 --> 00:16:33.630
but empty lodgings andunfurnished walls,

300
00:16:33.630 --> 00:16:36.670
unpeopled offices,untrodden stones?

301
00:16:37.870 --> 00:16:40.730
And what hear there forwelcome but my groans?

302
00:16:43.830 --> 00:16:44.900
Therefore commend me.

303
00:16:46.870 --> 00:16:47.970
Let him not come there

304
00:16:47.970 --> 00:16:50.830
to seek out sorrow thatdwells everywhere.

305
00:16:55.230 --> 00:17:01.100
Desolate, desolate, will Ihence and die.

306
00:17:03.530 --> 00:17:06.330
The last leave of theetakes my weeping eye.

307
00:17:14.370 --> 00:17:16.600
My Lord Aumerle, is HarryHereford armed?

308
00:17:16.600 --> 00:17:19.670
Yea, at all points andlongs to enter in.

309
00:17:19.670 --> 00:17:21.830
The duke of Norfolk,sprightfully and bold,

310
00:17:21.830 --> 00:17:24.530
stays but the summons ofthe appellant's trumpet.

311
00:17:24.530 --> 00:17:26.700
Why, then, the championsare prepared

312
00:17:26.700 --> 00:17:28.970
and stay for nothing butHis Majesty's approach.

313
00:17:49.300 --> 00:17:51.770
Marshal, demand of yonderchampion

314
00:17:51.770 --> 00:17:53.930
the cause of his arrivalhere in arms.

315
00:17:53.930 --> 00:17:55.500
Ask him his name

316
00:17:55.500 --> 00:17:59.070
and orderly proceed toswear him in the justiceof his cause.

317
00:18:00.830 --> 00:18:02.770
In God's name and theking's,

318
00:18:02.770 --> 00:18:04.030
say who thou art

319
00:18:04.030 --> 00:18:07.070
and why thou comest thusknightly clad in arms,

320
00:18:07.070 --> 00:18:08.670
against what man thoucomest,

321
00:18:08.670 --> 00:18:10.100
and what thy quarrel.

322
00:18:10.100 --> 00:18:12.230
Speak truly on thyknighthood and thy oath,

323
00:18:12.230 --> 00:18:14.800
and so defend thee heavenand thy valor.

324
00:18:14.800 --> 00:18:17.670
My name is Thomas Mowbray,duke of Norfolk,

325
00:18:17.670 --> 00:18:20.030
who hither come engaged bymy oath--

326
00:18:20.030 --> 00:18:22.530
which God defend a knightshould violate--

327
00:18:22.530 --> 00:18:24.530
both to defend my loyaltyand truth

328
00:18:24.530 --> 00:18:27.470
to God, my king, and mysucceeding issue

329
00:18:27.470 --> 00:18:30.170
against the duke ofHereford that appeals me,

330
00:18:30.170 --> 00:18:33.030
and, by the grace of Godand this mine arm, toprove him,

331
00:18:33.030 --> 00:18:34.170
in defending of myself,

332
00:18:34.170 --> 00:18:37.930
a traitor to my God, myking, and me.

333
00:18:37.930 --> 00:18:40.530
And as I truly fight,defend me heaven.

334
00:18:45.970 --> 00:18:49.530
Marshal, demand of yonderknight in arms both who he is

335
00:18:49.530 --> 00:18:52.930
and why he cometh hither thusplated in habiliments of war,

336
00:18:52.930 --> 00:18:55.200
and formally, according toour law,

337
00:18:55.200 --> 00:18:57.670
depose him in the justiceof his cause.

338
00:18:59.330 --> 00:19:02.770
What is thy name, andwherefore comest thou hither

339
00:19:02.770 --> 00:19:05.270
before King Richard in hisroyal lists?

340
00:19:05.270 --> 00:19:08.370
Against whom comest thou,and what's thy quarrel?

341
00:19:08.370 --> 00:19:10.830
Speak like a true knight,so defend thee heaven.

342
00:19:10.830 --> 00:19:14.600
Harry of Hereford,Lancaster, and Derby am I,

343
00:19:15.600 --> 00:19:18.530
who ready here do stand inarms

344
00:19:18.530 --> 00:19:21.670
to prove, by God's graceand my body's valor,

345
00:19:21.670 --> 00:19:25.400
in lists on ThomasMowbray, duke of Norfolk,

346
00:19:25.400 --> 00:19:28.630
that he is a traitor, fouland dangerous,

347
00:19:28.630 --> 00:19:32.930
to God of heaven, KingRichard, and to me.

348
00:19:32.930 --> 00:19:35.300
And as I fight, defend meheaven.

349
00:19:37.300 --> 00:19:38.700
On pain of death,

350
00:19:38.700 --> 00:19:41.470
no person be so bold ordaring-hardy

351
00:19:41.470 --> 00:19:43.230
as to touch the lists

352
00:19:43.230 --> 00:19:46.230
except the marshal andsuch officers appointed

353
00:19:46.230 --> 00:19:48.930
to direct these fairdesigns.

354
00:19:48.930 --> 00:19:50.230
Lord marshal,

355
00:19:50.230 --> 00:19:52.400
let me kiss my sovereign'shand

356
00:19:52.400 --> 00:19:54.800
and bow my knee before HisMajesty,

357
00:19:54.800 --> 00:19:56.170
for Mowbray and myself

358
00:19:56.170 --> 00:20:00.830
are like two men that vowa long and wearypilgrimage.

359
00:20:00.830 --> 00:20:02.630
Then let us take aceremonious leave

360
00:20:02.630 --> 00:20:04.870
and loving farewell of ourseveral friends.

361
00:20:08.600 --> 00:20:10.700
The appellant in all dutygreets Your Highness

362
00:20:10.700 --> 00:20:13.230
and craves to kiss yourhand and take his leave.

363
00:20:13.230 --> 00:20:16.370
We will descend and foldhim in our arms.

364
00:20:26.770 --> 00:20:29.130
Cousin of Hereford, as thycause is right,

365
00:20:29.130 --> 00:20:31.670
so be thy fortune in thisroyal fight.

366
00:20:31.670 --> 00:20:34.970
Farewell, my blood, whichif today thou shed,

367
00:20:34.970 --> 00:20:38.670
lament we may, but notrevenge thee dead.

368
00:20:38.670 --> 00:20:42.000
Oh, let no noble eyeprofane a tear for me

369
00:20:42.000 --> 00:20:44.700
if I be gored withMowbray's spear.

370
00:20:44.700 --> 00:20:47.630
As confident as is thefalcon's flight against a bird

371
00:20:47.630 --> 00:20:49.100
do I with Mowbray fight.

372
00:20:50.430 --> 00:20:52.470
My loving lord, I take myleave of you;

373
00:20:55.400 --> 00:20:59.400
of you, my noble cousin,Lord Aumerle.

374
00:20:59.400 --> 00:21:02.470
Not sick, although I haveto do with death,

375
00:21:02.470 --> 00:21:05.570
but lusty, young, andcheerly drawing breath.

376
00:21:08.600 --> 00:21:10.230
Lo, as at English feasts,

377
00:21:10.230 --> 00:21:15.670
so I regreet the daintiestlast to make the end mostsweet.

378
00:21:15.670 --> 00:21:18.500
Oh, thou, the earthlyauthor of my blood,

379
00:21:18.500 --> 00:21:21.170
whose youthful spirit inme regenerate,

380
00:21:21.170 --> 00:21:23.900
doth with a twofold vigorlift me up

381
00:21:23.900 --> 00:21:26.930
to reach at victory abovemy head.

382
00:21:26.930 --> 00:21:30.530
Add proof unto mine armorwith thy prayers,

383
00:21:30.530 --> 00:21:33.770
and with thy blessingssteel my lance's point

384
00:21:33.770 --> 00:21:36.230
that it may enterMowbray's waxen coat

385
00:21:36.230 --> 00:21:39.000
and furbish new the nameof John a Gaunt,

386
00:21:39.000 --> 00:21:42.230
even in the lusty haviorof his son.

387
00:21:42.230 --> 00:21:45.200
God in thy good cause makethee prosperous.

388
00:21:45.200 --> 00:21:48.270
Be swift like lightning inthe execution

389
00:21:48.270 --> 00:21:50.500
and let thy blows, doublyredoubled,

390
00:21:50.500 --> 00:21:52.330
fall like amazing thunder

391
00:21:52.330 --> 00:21:55.470
on the casque of thyadverse pernicious enemy.

392
00:21:55.470 --> 00:21:57.530
Rouse up thy youthfulblood.

393
00:21:57.530 --> 00:21:59.800
Be valiant, and live.

394
00:22:01.400 --> 00:22:04.400
Mine innocency and SaintGeorge to thrive.

395
00:22:05.930 --> 00:22:09.700
However God or fortune castmy lot, there lives or dies,

396
00:22:09.700 --> 00:22:11.300
true to King Richard'sthrone,

397
00:22:11.300 --> 00:22:15.670
a loyal, just, and uprightgentleman.

398
00:22:15.670 --> 00:22:17.770
Never did captive with afreer heart

399
00:22:17.770 --> 00:22:19.270
cast off his chains ofbondage

400
00:22:19.270 --> 00:22:21.630
and embrace his goldenuncontrolled enfranchisement

401
00:22:21.630 --> 00:22:24.470
more than my dancing souldoth celebrate

402
00:22:24.470 --> 00:22:27.300
this feast of battle withmine adversary.

403
00:22:27.300 --> 00:22:29.570
Most mighty liege and mycompanion peers,

404
00:22:29.570 --> 00:22:32.130
take from my mouth thewish of happy years.

405
00:22:32.130 --> 00:22:35.970
As gentle and as jocund asto jest go I to fight.

406
00:22:35.970 --> 00:22:38.470
Truth hath a quiet breast.

407
00:22:38.470 --> 00:22:40.230
Farewell, my lord.

408
00:22:40.230 --> 00:22:43.930
Securely I espy virtuewith valor couched inthine eye.

409
00:22:45.770 --> 00:22:47.600
Order the trial, marshal,and begin.

410
00:22:51.970 --> 00:22:54.900
Harry of Hereford,Lancaster, and Derby,

411
00:22:54.900 --> 00:22:58.170
receive thy lance and Goddefend the right.

412
00:23:02.470 --> 00:23:06.030
Strong as a tower in hope,I cry amen.

413
00:23:07.800 --> 00:23:10.600
Go bear this lance toThomas, duke of Norfolk.

414
00:23:15.730 --> 00:23:19.400
Herald Harry of Hereford,Lancaster, and Derby

415
00:23:19.400 --> 00:23:24.030
stands here for God, hissovereign, and himself,

416
00:23:24.030 --> 00:23:27.030
on pain to be found falseand recreant,

417
00:23:27.030 --> 00:23:30.330
to prove the duke ofNorfolk, Thomas Mowbray

418
00:23:30.330 --> 00:23:34.870
a traitor to his God, hisking, and him,

419
00:23:34.870 --> 00:23:37.870
and dares him to setforward to the fight.

420
00:23:37.870 --> 00:23:40.470
Here standeth ThomasMowbray, duke of Norfolk,

421
00:23:40.470 --> 00:23:43.000
on pain to be found falseand recreant,

422
00:23:43.000 --> 00:23:44.270
both to defend himself

423
00:23:44.270 --> 00:23:47.930
and to approve Henry ofHereford, Lancaster, and Derby

424
00:23:47.930 --> 00:23:51.370
to God, his sovereign, andto him disloyal,

425
00:23:51.370 --> 00:23:53.400
courageously and with afree desire,

426
00:23:53.400 --> 00:23:55.730
attending but the signalto begin.

427
00:23:59.430 --> 00:24:03.630
Sound trumpets and setforward, combatants.

428
00:24:10.500 --> 00:24:11.670
Stay!

429
00:24:11.670 --> 00:24:13.600
The king hath thrown hiswarder down.

430
00:24:13.600 --> 00:24:16.370
Let them lay by theirhelmets and their spears

431
00:24:16.370 --> 00:24:19.400
and both return back totheir chairs again.

432
00:24:19.400 --> 00:24:20.470
Withdraw with us.

433
00:24:21.500 --> 00:24:22.900
And let the trumpets sound

434
00:24:22.900 --> 00:24:25.070
while we return thesedukes what we decree.

435
00:24:27.470 --> 00:24:28.470
Draw near

436
00:24:30.530 --> 00:24:32.300
and list what with ourcouncil we have done.

437
00:24:35.530 --> 00:24:37.530
For that our kingdom'searth should not be soiled

438
00:24:37.530 --> 00:24:40.000
with that dear blood whichit hath fostered,

439
00:24:40.000 --> 00:24:41.970
and for our eyes do hatethe dire aspect

440
00:24:41.970 --> 00:24:45.200
of civil wounds ploughedup with neighbors' sword,

441
00:24:45.200 --> 00:24:47.300
and for we think the eaglewinged pride

442
00:24:47.300 --> 00:24:50.130
of sky aspiring andambitious thoughts,

443
00:24:50.130 --> 00:24:54.300
with rival hating envy, seton you to wake our peace--

444
00:24:54.300 --> 00:24:55.630
which in our country'scradle

445
00:24:55.630 --> 00:24:58.270
draws the sweet infantbreath of gentle sleep--

446
00:24:58.270 --> 00:25:02.000
which so roused up withboisterous, untuned drums,

447
00:25:02.000 --> 00:25:04.730
with harsh resoundingtrumpets' dreadful bray

448
00:25:04.730 --> 00:25:07.370
and grating shock ofwrathful iron arms,

449
00:25:07.370 --> 00:25:10.870
might from our quietconfines fright fair peace

450
00:25:10.870 --> 00:25:14.770
and make us wade even inour kindred's blood.

451
00:25:14.770 --> 00:25:18.000
Therefore, we banish youour territories.

452
00:25:18.000 --> 00:25:21.430
You, cousin Hereford, uponpain of life,

453
00:25:21.430 --> 00:25:23.970
till twice five summershave enriched our fields

454
00:25:23.970 --> 00:25:26.930
shall not regreet our fairdominions

455
00:25:26.930 --> 00:25:30.300
but tread the strangerpaths of banishment.

456
00:25:31.770 --> 00:25:33.130
Thy will be done.

457
00:25:35.070 --> 00:25:37.330
This must my comfort be:

458
00:25:37.330 --> 00:25:40.400
that sun that warms youhere shall shine on me,

459
00:25:40.400 --> 00:25:43.530
and those his golden beamsto you here lent

460
00:25:43.530 --> 00:25:46.430
shall point on me and gildmy banishment.

461
00:25:48.030 --> 00:25:51.770
Norfolk, for thee remainsa heavier doom,

462
00:25:51.770 --> 00:25:54.500
which I with someunwillingness pronounce.

463
00:25:54.500 --> 00:25:57.730
The sly, slow hours shallnot determinate

464
00:25:57.730 --> 00:26:00.430
the dateless limit of thydear exile.

465
00:26:00.430 --> 00:26:03.370
The hopeless word of"never to return"

466
00:26:03.370 --> 00:26:06.730
breathe I against thee,upon pain of life.

467
00:26:09.370 --> 00:26:12.300
A heavy sentence, my mostsovereign liege,

468
00:26:12.300 --> 00:26:16.230
and all unlooked for fromYour Highness' mouth.

469
00:26:16.230 --> 00:26:17.570
A dearer merit,

470
00:26:17.570 --> 00:26:20.570
not so deep a maim as tobe cast forth in thecommon air,

471
00:26:20.570 --> 00:26:23.800
have I deserved at YourHighness' hands.

472
00:26:23.800 --> 00:26:25.970
The language I havelearned these 40 years,

473
00:26:25.970 --> 00:26:28.730
my native English, now Imust forego.

474
00:26:28.730 --> 00:26:29.800
And now my tongue's use

475
00:26:29.800 --> 00:26:32.370
is to me no more than anunstringed viol or a harp

476
00:26:32.370 --> 00:26:35.400
or like a cunninginstrument cased up or,being open,

477
00:26:35.400 --> 00:26:39.730
put into his hands thatknows no touch to tune theharmony.

478
00:26:39.730 --> 00:26:42.530
Within my mouth you haveenjailed my tongue,

479
00:26:42.530 --> 00:26:44.730
doubly portcullised withmy teeth and lips,

480
00:26:44.730 --> 00:26:46.870
and dull, unfeeling,barren ignorance

481
00:26:46.870 --> 00:26:48.900
is made my jailer toattend on me.

482
00:26:50.030 --> 00:26:52.200
I am too old to fawn upona nurse,

483
00:26:52.200 --> 00:26:55.070
too far in years to be apupil now.

484
00:26:55.070 --> 00:26:58.230
What is thy sentence thenbut speechless death,

485
00:26:58.230 --> 00:27:01.970
which robs my tongue frombreathing native breath?

486
00:27:01.970 --> 00:27:04.270
It boots thee not to becompassionate.

487
00:27:04.270 --> 00:27:07.500
After our sentence,plaining comes too late.

488
00:27:07.500 --> 00:27:11.570
Then thus I turn me frommy country's light

489
00:27:11.570 --> 00:27:15.500
to dwell in solemn shadesof endless night.

490
00:27:15.500 --> 00:27:17.300
Return again,

491
00:27:17.300 --> 00:27:18.800
and take an oath withthee.

492
00:27:20.170 --> 00:27:22.700
Lay on our royal swordyour banished hands.

493
00:27:24.670 --> 00:27:26.830
Swear by the duty that youowe to God--

494
00:27:26.830 --> 00:27:29.000
our part therein we banishwith yourselves--

495
00:27:29.000 --> 00:27:31.270
to keep the oath that weadminister.

496
00:27:31.270 --> 00:27:34.830
You never shall, so helpyou truth and God,

497
00:27:34.830 --> 00:27:37.130
embrace each other's lovein banishment;

498
00:27:37.130 --> 00:27:39.600
nor never look upon eachother's face;

499
00:27:39.600 --> 00:27:43.030
nor never write, regreet,nor reconcile

500
00:27:43.030 --> 00:27:46.300
this louring tempest ofyour homebred hate;

501
00:27:46.300 --> 00:27:48.830
nor never by advisedpurpose meet

502
00:27:48.830 --> 00:27:52.170
to plot, contrive, orcomplot any ill

503
00:27:52.170 --> 00:27:56.770
against us, our state, oursubjects, or our land.

504
00:27:56.770 --> 00:27:57.970
I swear.

505
00:27:57.970 --> 00:27:59.830
And I, to keep all this.

506
00:28:04.270 --> 00:28:07.730
Norfolk, so far as to mineenemy,

507
00:28:07.730 --> 00:28:09.570
by this time, had the kingpermitted us,

508
00:28:09.570 --> 00:28:12.100
one of our souls hadwandered in the air,

509
00:28:12.100 --> 00:28:14.830
banished this frailsepulcher of our flesh,

510
00:28:14.830 --> 00:28:18.230
as now our flesh isbanished from this land.

