768
00:40:56.370 --> 00:40:59.530
this land of such dearsouls;

769
00:40:59.530 --> 00:41:01.630
this dear, dear land--

770
00:41:01.630 --> 00:41:04.400
dear for her reputationthrough the world--

771
00:41:04.400 --> 00:41:08.470
is now leased out--

772
00:41:08.470 --> 00:41:11.300
I die pronouncing it--

773
00:41:11.300 --> 00:41:14.400
like to a tenement orpelting farm.

774
00:41:14.400 --> 00:41:17.500
England, bound in with thetriumphant sea

775
00:41:17.500 --> 00:41:22.400
whose rocky shore beatsback the envious siege ofwatery Neptune,

776
00:41:22.400 --> 00:41:25.300
is now bound in withshame,

777
00:41:25.300 --> 00:41:28.670
with inky blots and rottenparchment bonds.

778
00:41:30.470 --> 00:41:33.270
That England that was wontto conquer others

779
00:41:33.270 --> 00:41:36.730
hath made a shamefulconquest of itself.

780
00:41:39.170 --> 00:41:45.200
Ah, would the scandalvanish with my life,

781
00:41:46.530 --> 00:41:51.700
how happy then were myensuing death.

782
00:41:53.770 --> 00:41:55.570
The king is come.

783
00:41:55.570 --> 00:41:57.170
Deal mildly with hisyouth,

784
00:41:57.170 --> 00:42:00.070
for young, hot colts beingraged do rage the more.

785
00:42:03.230 --> 00:42:05.300
How fares our noble UncleLancaster?

786
00:42:05.300 --> 00:42:06.700
What comfort, man?

787
00:42:06.700 --> 00:42:08.700
How is't with aged Gaunt?

788
00:42:08.700 --> 00:42:11.430
Oh, how that name befitsmy composition.

789
00:42:12.100 --> 00:42:15.400
Old Gaunt indeed, andgaunt in being old.

790
00:42:15.400 --> 00:42:18.900
Within me grief has kept atedious fast.

791
00:42:18.900 --> 00:42:21.830
And who abstains from meatthat is not gaunt?

792
00:42:21.830 --> 00:42:24.730
For sleeping England longtime have I watched.

793
00:42:24.730 --> 00:42:26.600
Watching breeds leanness.

794
00:42:26.600 --> 00:42:29.030
Leanness is all gaunt.

795
00:42:29.030 --> 00:42:32.730
The pleasure that somefathers feed upon is mystrict fast.

796
00:42:32.730 --> 00:42:35.800
I mean my children'slooks.

797
00:42:35.800 --> 00:42:40.030
And therein fasting hastthou made me gaunt.

798
00:42:40.030 --> 00:42:43.130
Gaunt am I for the grave,gaunt as a grave,

799
00:42:43.130 --> 00:42:45.830
whose hollow womb inheritsnaught but bones.

800
00:42:45.830 --> 00:42:48.600
Can sick men play sonicely with their names?

801
00:42:48.600 --> 00:42:52.200
No, misery makes sport tomock itself.

802
00:42:52.200 --> 00:42:54.570
Since thou dost seek tokill my name in me,

803
00:42:54.570 --> 00:42:57.670
I mock my name, greatKing, to flatter thee.

804
00:42:57.670 --> 00:42:59.730
Should dying men flatterwith those that live?

805
00:42:59.730 --> 00:43:01.430
No, men living flatterthose that die.

806
00:43:01.430 --> 00:43:03.530
Thou, now a-dying, say'stthou flatterest me.

807
00:43:03.530 --> 00:43:05.870
Oh, no, thou diest, thoughI the sicker be.

808
00:43:05.870 --> 00:43:07.430
I am in health.

809
00:43:07.430 --> 00:43:09.700
I breathe and see thee ill.

810
00:43:09.700 --> 00:43:12.900
Now He that made me knowsI see thee ill,

811
00:43:12.900 --> 00:43:17.200
ill in myself to see andin thee seeing ill.

812
00:43:17.200 --> 00:43:20.370
Thy deathbed is no lesserthan thy land

813
00:43:20.370 --> 00:43:23.270
wherein thou liest inreputation sick.

814
00:43:23.270 --> 00:43:26.430
And thou, too carelesspatient as thou art,

815
00:43:26.430 --> 00:43:28.370
commit'st thy anointedbody

816
00:43:28.370 --> 00:43:32.870
to the cure of thosephysicians that firstwounded thee.

817
00:43:34.500 --> 00:43:37.270
A thousand flatterers sitwithin thy crown,

818
00:43:37.270 --> 00:43:39.300
whose compass is no biggerthan thy head.

819
00:43:39.300 --> 00:43:41.170
And yet, encaged in sosmall a verge,

820
00:43:41.170 --> 00:43:45.170
the waste is no whitlesser than thy land.

821
00:43:45.170 --> 00:43:49.400
Oh, had thy grandsire witha prophet's eye

822
00:43:49.400 --> 00:43:53.530
seen how his son's sonshould destroy his sons,

823
00:43:53.530 --> 00:43:57.070
from forth thy reach hewould have laid thy shame,

824
00:43:57.070 --> 00:43:59.800
deposing thee before thouwert possessed,

825
00:43:59.800 --> 00:44:04.500
which art possessed now todepose thyself.

826
00:44:04.500 --> 00:44:07.600
Why, cousin, wert thouregent of the world,

827
00:44:07.600 --> 00:44:11.030
it were a shame to letthis land by lease.

828
00:44:11.030 --> 00:44:12.930
And for thy world enjoyingbut this land,

829
00:44:12.930 --> 00:44:17.200
is it not more than shameto shame it so?

830
00:44:17.200 --> 00:44:19.300
Landlord of England artthou now,

831
00:44:19.300 --> 00:44:20.770
not king.

832
00:44:20.770 --> 00:44:22.870
Thy state of law isbondslave to the law.

833
00:44:22.870 --> 00:44:23.870
And thou--

834
00:44:23.870 --> 00:44:26.530
A lunatic, lean-wittedfool,

835
00:44:26.530 --> 00:44:28.970
presuming on an ague'sprivilege,

836
00:44:28.970 --> 00:44:32.570
darest with thy frozenadmonition make pale ourcheek,

837
00:44:32.570 --> 00:44:34.500
chasing the royal bloodwith fury

838
00:44:34.500 --> 00:44:35.870
from his native residence.

839
00:44:35.870 --> 00:44:38.330
Now, by my seat's rightroyal majesty,

840
00:44:38.330 --> 00:44:41.230
wert thou not brother togreat Edward's son,

841
00:44:41.230 --> 00:44:43.870
this tongue that runs soroundly in thy head

842
00:44:43.870 --> 00:44:46.200
should run thy head fromthy unreverent shoulders.

843
00:44:47.730 --> 00:44:51.200
Oh, spare me not, mybrother Edward's son.

844
00:44:52.270 --> 00:44:55.730
For that I was his fatherEdward's son.

845
00:44:59.270 --> 00:45:02.230
That blood already, likethe pelican,

846
00:45:02.230 --> 00:45:05.670
hast thou tapped out anddrunkenly caroused.

847
00:45:06.600 --> 00:45:10.470
My brother Gloucester,plain well-meaning soul,

848
00:45:10.470 --> 00:45:13.630
whom fair befall in heavenamongst happy souls,

849
00:45:13.630 --> 00:45:15.800
may be a precedent andwitness good

850
00:45:15.800 --> 00:45:20.630
that thou respect'st notspilling Edward's blood.

851
00:45:24.000 --> 00:45:27.370
Joined with the presentsickness that I have,

852
00:45:27.370 --> 00:45:31.770
and thy unkindness be likecrooked age

853
00:45:31.770 --> 00:45:34.030
to crop at once a too longwithered flower.

854
00:45:37.200 --> 00:45:39.770
Live in thy shame,

855
00:45:39.770 --> 00:45:42.370
but die not shamewith thee.

856
00:45:43.800 --> 00:45:47.600
These words hereafter thytormentors be.

857
00:45:53.630 --> 00:46:00.100
Convey me to my bed, thento my grave.

858
00:46:03.300 --> 00:46:10.130
Love they to live thatlove and honor have.

859
00:46:18.330 --> 00:46:21.670
And let them die that ageand sullens have,

860
00:46:21.670 --> 00:46:23.830
for both hast thou, andboth become the grave.

861
00:46:23.830 --> 00:46:25.170
I do beseech Your Majesty.

862
00:46:25.170 --> 00:46:28.270
Impute his words to waywardsickliness and age in him.

863
00:46:28.270 --> 00:46:30.270
He loves you, on my life,

864
00:46:30.270 --> 00:46:32.330
and holds you dear asHarry, duke of Hereford,

865
00:46:32.330 --> 00:46:33.330
were he here.

866
00:46:33.330 --> 00:46:34.430
Right, you say true.

867
00:46:34.430 --> 00:46:36.600
As Hereford's love, sohis.

868
00:46:36.600 --> 00:46:38.130
As theirs, so mine.

869
00:46:38.130 --> 00:46:39.630
And all be as it is.

870
00:46:39.630 --> 00:46:44.530
My liege, old Gauntcommends him to YourMajesty.

871
00:46:44.530 --> 00:46:45.630
What says he?

872
00:46:45.630 --> 00:46:47.700
Nay, nothing.

873
00:46:47.700 --> 00:46:49.830
All is said.

874
00:46:49.830 --> 00:46:53.400
His tongue is now astringless instrument.

875
00:46:53.400 --> 00:46:58.000
Words, life, and all, oldLancaster hath spent.

876
00:46:58.000 --> 00:47:00.600
Be York the next that mustbe bankrupt so.

877
00:47:00.600 --> 00:47:02.700
Though death be poor, itends a mortal woe.

878
00:47:06.200 --> 00:47:08.870
The ripest fruit firstfalls,

879
00:47:10.300 --> 00:47:12.970
and so doth he.

880
00:47:12.970 --> 00:47:15.770
His time is spent.

881
00:47:15.770 --> 00:47:17.830
Our pilgrimage must be.

882
00:47:19.700 --> 00:47:21.270
So much for that.

883
00:47:21.270 --> 00:47:24.000
Now for our Irish wars.

884
00:47:24.000 --> 00:47:27.500
We must supplant thoserough, rugheaded kerns,

885
00:47:27.500 --> 00:47:29.000
which live like venom

886
00:47:29.000 --> 00:47:31.730
where no venom else but onlythey have privilege to live.

887
00:47:31.730 --> 00:47:34.770
And for these great affairsdo ask some charge.

888
00:47:34.770 --> 00:47:37.000
Towards our assistance wedo seize to us

889
00:47:37.000 --> 00:47:38.900
the plate, coin, revenues,and moveables

890
00:47:38.900 --> 00:47:40.970
whereof our Uncle Gauntdid stand possessed.

891
00:47:40.970 --> 00:47:43.000
How long must I bepatient?

892
00:47:43.000 --> 00:47:47.100
Ah, how long shall tenderduty make me suffer wrong?

893
00:47:47.100 --> 00:47:48.870
Not Gloucester's death,

894
00:47:48.870 --> 00:47:51.270
nor Hereford's banishment,not Gaunt's rebukes,

895
00:47:51.270 --> 00:47:52.830
nor England's privatewrongs,

896
00:47:52.830 --> 00:47:55.100
nor the prevention of poorBolingbroke about hismarriage,

897
00:47:55.100 --> 00:47:56.100
nor my own disgrace,

898
00:47:56.100 --> 00:47:58.100
have ever made me sour mypatient cheek

899
00:47:58.100 --> 00:48:01.670
or bend one wrinkle on mysovereign's face.

900
00:48:01.670 --> 00:48:04.870
I am the last of nobleEdward's sons,

901
00:48:04.870 --> 00:48:07.730
of whom thy father, princeof Wales, was first.

902
00:48:07.730 --> 00:48:10.430
In war was never lionraged more fierce,

903
00:48:10.430 --> 00:48:12.630
in peace was never gentlelamb more mild,

904
00:48:12.630 --> 00:48:17.030
than was that young andprincely gentleman.

905
00:48:17.030 --> 00:48:19.500
His face thou hast,

906
00:48:19.500 --> 00:48:20.500
for even so looked he,

907
00:48:20.500 --> 00:48:22.130
accomplished with thenumber of thy hours.

908
00:48:22.130 --> 00:48:23.300
But when he frowned,

909
00:48:23.300 --> 00:48:25.330
it was against the Frenchand not against his friends.

910
00:48:25.330 --> 00:48:27.770
His noble hand did winwhat he did spend

911
00:48:27.770 --> 00:48:28.800
and spent not that

912
00:48:28.800 --> 00:48:30.800
which his triumphantfather's hand had won.

913
00:48:30.800 --> 00:48:33.000
His hands were guilty ofno kindred blood,

914
00:48:33.000 --> 00:48:36.300
but bloody with theenemies of his kin.

915
00:48:36.300 --> 00:48:38.830
Oh, Richard.

916
00:48:38.830 --> 00:48:40.730
York is too far gone withgrief,

917
00:48:40.730 --> 00:48:42.400
or else he never wouldcompare between.

918
00:48:42.400 --> 00:48:45.470
Why, Uncle, what's thematter?

919
00:48:45.470 --> 00:48:46.700
Oh, my liege.

920
00:48:48.900 --> 00:48:49.930
Pardon me, if you please.

921
00:48:49.930 --> 00:48:51.370
If not, I, pleased not tobe pardoned,

922
00:48:51.370 --> 00:48:52.930
am content withal.

923
00:48:52.930 --> 00:48:55.230
Seek you to seize andgripe into your hands

924
00:48:55.230 --> 00:48:57.730
the royalties and rightsof banished Hereford?

925
00:48:57.730 --> 00:48:58.970
Is not Gaunt dead,

926
00:48:58.970 --> 00:49:00.530
and doth not Herefordlive?

927
00:49:00.530 --> 00:49:02.600
Was not Gaunt just, and isnot Harry true?

928
00:49:02.600 --> 00:49:04.870
Did not the one deserve tohave an heir?

929
00:49:04.870 --> 00:49:07.170
Is not his heir awell-deserving son?

930
00:49:07.170 --> 00:49:10.030
Take Hereford's rightsaway

931
00:49:10.030 --> 00:49:14.400
and take from time his chartersand his customary rights,

932
00:49:14.400 --> 00:49:16.200
let not tomorrow thenensue today,

933
00:49:16.200 --> 00:49:17.630
be not thyself.

934
00:49:17.630 --> 00:49:21.670
For how art thou a kingbut by fair sequence andsuccession?

935
00:49:21.670 --> 00:49:25.030
Now, afore God-- Godforbid I say true--

936
00:49:25.030 --> 00:49:28.070
if you do wrongfully seizeHereford's rights,

937
00:49:28.070 --> 00:49:29.670
call in the letters patentthat he hath

938
00:49:29.670 --> 00:49:31.270
by his attorneys generalto sue his livery,

939
00:49:31.270 --> 00:49:32.770
and deny his offeredhomage,

940
00:49:32.770 --> 00:49:35.200
you pluck a thousanddangers on your head.

941
00:49:35.200 --> 00:49:37.900
You lose a thousandwell-disposed hearts

942
00:49:37.900 --> 00:49:39.930
and prick my tenderpatience

943
00:49:39.930 --> 00:49:42.600
to such thoughts as honorand allegiance cannot think.

944
00:49:42.600 --> 00:49:43.600
Think what you will.

945
00:49:43.600 --> 00:49:45.030
We seize into our hands

946
00:49:45.030 --> 00:49:47.470
his plate, his goods, hismoney, and his lands.

947
00:49:51.300 --> 00:49:53.970
I'll not be by the while.

948
00:49:53.970 --> 00:49:56.200
My liege, farewell.

949
00:49:56.200 --> 00:49:59.330
What will ensue hereof,there's none can tell.

950
00:49:59.330 --> 00:50:02.470
But by bad courses may beunderstood

951
00:50:02.470 --> 00:50:05.030
that their events cannever fall out good.

952
00:50:08.730 --> 00:50:10.800
Go, Bushy, to the earl ofWiltshire straight.

953
00:50:10.800 --> 00:50:12.830
Bid him repair to us to ElyHouse to see this business.

954
00:50:14.000 --> 00:50:15.900
Tomorrow next we will forIreland,

955
00:50:15.900 --> 00:50:18.200
and 'tis time, I trow.

956
00:50:18.200 --> 00:50:21.300
And we create, in absenceof ourself,

957
00:50:21.300 --> 00:50:24.170
our Uncle York lordgovernor of England,

958
00:50:24.170 --> 00:50:29.530
for he is just and alwaysloved us well.

959
00:50:29.530 --> 00:50:31.700
Come on, our queen.

960
00:50:31.700 --> 00:50:33.100
Tomorrow must we part.

961
00:50:33.100 --> 00:50:35.270
Be merry,

962
00:50:35.270 --> 00:50:37.900
for our time of stay isshort.

963
00:50:52.400 --> 00:50:57.170
Well, lords, the duke ofLancaster is dead.

964
00:50:57.170 --> 00:51:00.170
And living, too, for nowhis son is duke.

965
00:51:00.170 --> 00:51:02.830
Barely in title, not inrevenues.

966
00:51:02.830 --> 00:51:06.100
Richly in both, if justicehad her right.

967
00:51:06.100 --> 00:51:08.900
My heart is great, but itmust break with silence,

968
00:51:08.900 --> 00:51:11.130
ere't be disburdened witha liberal tongue.

969
00:51:11.130 --> 00:51:12.770
Nay, speak thy mind,

970
00:51:12.770 --> 00:51:15.070
and let him ne'er speakmore

971
00:51:15.070 --> 00:51:17.800
that speaks thy wordsagain to do thee harm.

972
00:51:17.800 --> 00:51:20.300
Tends that thou wouldstspeak to the duke ofHereford?

973
00:51:20.300 --> 00:51:22.370
If it be so, out with itboldly, man.

974
00:51:22.370 --> 00:51:24.370
Quick is mine ear to hearof good towards him.

975
00:51:24.370 --> 00:51:26.230
No good at all that I cando for him,

976
00:51:26.230 --> 00:51:27.970
unless you call it good topity him,

977
00:51:27.970 --> 00:51:30.100
bereft and gelded of hispatrimony.

978
00:51:30.100 --> 00:51:31.600
Now, afore God,

979
00:51:31.600 --> 00:51:35.070
'tis shame such wrongs areborne in him,

980
00:51:35.070 --> 00:51:37.770
a royal prince,

981
00:51:37.770 --> 00:51:42.630
and many moe of nobleblood in this decliningland.

982
00:51:48.430 --> 00:51:52.830
The king is not himself,but basely led byflatterers.

983
00:51:52.830 --> 00:51:54.270
And what they will inform,

984
00:51:54.270 --> 00:51:56.430
merely in hate against anyof us all,

985
00:51:56.430 --> 00:51:59.370
that will the king severelyprosecute 'gainst us,

986
00:51:59.370 --> 00:52:01.830
our lives, our children,and our heirs.

987
00:52:01.830 --> 00:52:03.630
The commons hath he pilledwith grievous taxes

988
00:52:03.630 --> 00:52:05.170
and quite lost theirhearts.

989
00:52:05.170 --> 00:52:07.730
The nobles hath he finedfor ancient quarrels

990
00:52:07.730 --> 00:52:08.830
and quite lost theirhearts.

991
00:52:08.830 --> 00:52:11.130
And daily new exactionsare devised

992
00:52:11.130 --> 00:52:14.170
as blanks, benevolences,and I wot not what.

993
00:52:14.170 --> 00:52:16.670
But what, o' God's name,doth become of this?

994
00:52:16.670 --> 00:52:20.730
Wars have not wasted it,for warred he hath not,

995
00:52:20.730 --> 00:52:23.230
but basely yielded uponcompromise

996
00:52:23.230 --> 00:52:26.100
that which his noble ancestorsachieved with blows.

997
00:52:26.100 --> 00:52:30.370
More hath he spent inpeace than they in wars.

998
00:52:30.370 --> 00:52:32.600
The earl of Wiltshire haththe realm in farm.

999
00:52:32.600 --> 00:52:35.130
The king's grown bankrupt,like a broken man.

1000
00:52:35.130 --> 00:52:37.970
Reproach and dissolutionhangeth over him.

1001
00:52:37.970 --> 00:52:39.930
He hath not money forthese Irish wars,

1002
00:52:39.930 --> 00:52:42.400
his burdenous taxationsnotwithstanding,

1003
00:52:42.400 --> 00:52:44.670
but by the robbing of thebanished duke--

1004
00:52:44.670 --> 00:52:45.730
His noble kinsman.

1005
00:52:48.330 --> 00:52:51.900
Oh, most degenerate king.

1006
00:52:57.630 --> 00:52:59.630
But, lords, we hear thisfearful tempest sing,

1007
00:52:59.630 --> 00:53:01.700
yet seek no shelter toavoid the storm.

1008
00:53:01.700 --> 00:53:04.100
We see the wind sit soreupon our sails,

1009
00:53:04.100 --> 00:53:07.570
and yet we strike not, butsecurely perish.

1010
00:53:07.570 --> 00:53:09.470
We see the very wreck thatwe must suffer,

1011
00:53:09.470 --> 00:53:11.470
and unavoided is thedanger now

1012
00:53:11.470 --> 00:53:13.730
for suffering so thecauses of our wreck.

1013
00:53:13.730 --> 00:53:15.830
Not so.

1014
00:53:15.830 --> 00:53:22.700
Even through the hollow eyesof death I spy life peering,

1015
00:53:22.700 --> 00:53:25.670
but I dare not say hownear the tidings of ourcomfort is.

1016
00:53:25.670 --> 00:53:27.170
Nay, let us share thythoughts,

1017
00:53:27.170 --> 00:53:28.170
as thou dost ours.

1018
00:53:28.170 --> 00:53:29.830
Be confident to speak,Northumberland.

1019
00:53:29.830 --> 00:53:31.170
We three are but thyself.

1020
00:53:31.170 --> 00:53:32.170
And, speaking so,

1021
00:53:32.170 --> 00:53:34.270
thy words are but asthoughts.

1022
00:53:34.270 --> 00:53:36.570
Therefore, be bold.

1023
00:53:37.870 --> 00:53:39.830
Then thus.

1024
00:53:39.830 --> 00:53:42.530
I have from Le Port Blanc,a bay in Brittany,

1025
00:53:42.530 --> 00:53:44.930
received intelligence thatHarry, duke of Hereford;

1026
00:53:44.930 --> 00:53:46.400
Rainold Lord Cobham,

1027
00:53:46.400 --> 00:53:47.700
that late broke from theduke of Exeter;

1028
00:53:47.700 --> 00:53:49.800
his brother, archbishoplate of Canterbury;

1029
00:53:49.800 --> 00:53:51.730
Sir Thomas Erpingham; SirJohn Ramston;

1030
00:53:51.730 --> 00:53:54.430
Sir John Norbery; SirRobert Waterton; andFrancis Quoint--

1031
00:53:54.430 --> 00:53:57.100
all these well furnishedby the duke of Britain

1032
00:53:57.100 --> 00:53:58.400
with eight tall ships,

1033
00:53:58.400 --> 00:53:59.570
3,000 men of war--

1034
00:53:59.570 --> 00:54:01.400
are making hither with alldue expedience

1035
00:54:01.400 --> 00:54:04.130
and shortly mean to touchour northern shore.

1036
00:54:04.130 --> 00:54:05.430
Perhaps they had ere this,

1037
00:54:05.430 --> 00:54:06.470
but that they stay

1038
00:54:06.470 --> 00:54:08.670
the first departing of theking for Ireland.

1039
00:54:09.670 --> 00:54:14.230
If then we shall shake offour slavish yoke,

1040
00:54:14.230 --> 00:54:18.330
imp out our droopingcountry's broken wing,

1041
00:54:18.330 --> 00:54:22.270
redeem from broking pawnthe blemished crown,

1042
00:54:22.270 --> 00:54:25.370
wipe off the dust thathides our scepter's gilt,

1043
00:54:25.370 --> 00:54:29.800
and make high majesty looklike itself,

1044
00:54:29.800 --> 00:54:32.330
away with me in post toRavenspurgh.

1045
00:54:32.330 --> 00:54:35.900
But if you faint, asfearing to do so,

1046
00:54:35.900 --> 00:54:39.300
stay and be secret, andmyself will go.

1047
00:54:39.300 --> 00:54:40.570
To horse; to horse.

1048
00:54:40.570 --> 00:54:42.470
Urge doubts to them thatfear.

1049
00:54:42.470 --> 00:54:45.470
Hold out my horse, and Iwill first be there.

1050
00:54:45.470 --> 00:54:48.300
I know not what to do.

1051
00:54:48.300 --> 00:54:50.770
I would to God, so myuntruth had not provokedhim to it,

1052
00:54:50.770 --> 00:54:52.370
the king had cut off myhead with my brother's.

1053
00:54:52.370 --> 00:54:53.370
Uncle--

1054
00:54:53.370 --> 00:54:55.700
What, are there no postsdispatched for Ireland?

1055
00:54:55.700 --> 00:54:59.170
How shall we do for moneyfor these wars?

1056
00:54:59.170 --> 00:55:00.600
Come, Sister--

1057
00:55:00.600 --> 00:55:01.630
Cousin, I would say--

1058
00:55:01.630 --> 00:55:02.770
pray, pardon me.

1059
00:55:02.770 --> 00:55:04.270
Go, fellow.

1060
00:55:04.270 --> 00:55:05.500
Get thee home.

1061
00:55:05.500 --> 00:55:08.470
Provide some carts and bringaway the armor that is there.

1062
00:55:08.470 --> 00:55:11.300
Gentlemen, will you gomuster men?

1063
00:55:11.300 --> 00:55:14.700
If I know how or which wayto order these affairs

1064
00:55:14.700 --> 00:55:16.870
thus disorderly thrustinto my hands,

1065
00:55:16.870 --> 00:55:18.500
never believe me.

1066
00:55:18.500 --> 00:55:20.030
Both are my kinsmen.

1067
00:55:20.030 --> 00:55:21.530
The one is my sovereign,

1068
00:55:21.530 --> 00:55:23.230
whom both my oath and dutybids defend.

1069
00:55:23.230 --> 00:55:26.670
The other again is mykinsman, whom the kinghath wronged,

1070
00:55:26.670 --> 00:55:29.130
whom conscience and mykindred bids to right.

1071
00:55:31.930 --> 00:55:33.500
Well, somewhat we must do.

1072
00:55:33.500 --> 00:55:35.430
Come, cousin; I'll disposeof you.

1073
00:55:35.430 --> 00:55:37.830
Gentlemen, will you gomuster up your men

1074
00:55:37.830 --> 00:55:40.570
and meet me presently atBerkeley?

1075
00:55:40.570 --> 00:55:44.670
The wind sits fair fornews to go to Ireland,

1076
00:55:44.670 --> 00:55:46.130
but none returns.

1077
00:55:46.130 --> 00:55:48.430
For us to levy powerproportionable to the enemy

1078
00:55:48.430 --> 00:55:50.600
is all unpossible.

1079
00:55:50.600 --> 00:55:52.270
Besides, our nearness tothe king in love

1080
00:55:52.270 --> 00:55:54.030
is near the hate of thoselove not the king.

1081
00:55:54.030 --> 00:55:56.400
And that is the waveringcommons,

1082
00:55:56.400 --> 00:55:58.230
for their love lies intheir purses,

1083
00:55:58.230 --> 00:56:00.200
and whoso empties them byso much

1084
00:56:00.200 --> 00:56:01.770
fills their hearts withdeadly hate.

1085
00:56:01.770 --> 00:56:03.800
Wherein the king standsgenerally condemned.

1086
00:56:03.800 --> 00:56:07.030
If judgment lie in them,then so do we,

1087
00:56:07.030 --> 00:56:09.700
because we ever have beennear the king.

1088
00:56:09.700 --> 00:56:12.270
Well, I will for refugestraight to Bristol Castle.

1089
00:56:12.270 --> 00:56:14.100
The earl of Wiltshire isalready there.

1090
00:56:14.100 --> 00:56:15.700
Thither will I with you,

1091
00:56:15.700 --> 00:56:18.130
for little office will thehateful commons perform for us,

1092
00:56:18.130 --> 00:56:21.000
except like curs to tearus all to pieces.

1093
00:56:21.000 --> 00:56:22.330
Will you go along with us?

1094
00:56:22.330 --> 00:56:23.800
No.

1095
00:56:23.800 --> 00:56:25.470
I will to Ireland to HisMajesty.

1096
00:56:27.130 --> 00:56:28.130
Farewell.

1097
00:56:29.170 --> 00:56:31.500
If heart's presages be notvain,

1098
00:56:31.500 --> 00:56:34.500
we three here part thatne'er shall meet again.

1099
00:56:34.500 --> 00:56:37.470
That's as York thrives tobeat back Bolingbroke.

1100
00:56:37.470 --> 00:56:38.800
Alas, poor duke.

1101
00:56:38.800 --> 00:56:39.930
The task he undertakes

1102
00:56:39.930 --> 00:56:42.830
is numbering sands anddrinking oceans dry.

1103
00:56:42.830 --> 00:56:47.470
Where one on his sidefights, thousands will fly.

1104
00:56:47.470 --> 00:56:50.900
Farewell at once, foronce, for all, forever.

1105
00:56:50.900 --> 00:56:52.570
Well, we may meet again.

1106
00:56:53.930 --> 00:56:55.570
I fear me, never.

1107
00:56:59.530 --> 00:57:02.970
How far is it, my lord, toBerkeley now?

1108
00:57:02.970 --> 00:57:04.400
Believe me, noble lord,

1109
00:57:04.400 --> 00:57:07.130
I am a stranger here inGloucestershire.

1110
00:57:07.130 --> 00:57:09.930
These high, wild hills andrough, uneven ways

1111
00:57:09.930 --> 00:57:12.500
draws out our miles andmakes them wearisome.

1112
00:57:13.800 --> 00:57:16.300
And yet your fair discoursehath been as sugar,

1113
00:57:16.300 --> 00:57:19.930
making the hard way sweetand delectable.

1114
00:57:19.930 --> 00:57:21.270
But I bethink me what aweary way

1115
00:57:21.270 --> 00:57:23.270
from Ravenspurgh toCotswold will be found

1116
00:57:23.270 --> 00:57:26.030
in Ross and Willoughby,wanting your company,

1117
00:57:26.030 --> 00:57:28.200
which, I protest, hathvery much beguiled

1118
00:57:28.200 --> 00:57:32.230
the tediousness andprocess of my travel.

1119
00:57:32.230 --> 00:57:34.930
But theirs is sweetened bythe hope to have

1120
00:57:34.930 --> 00:57:36.470
the present benefit whichI possess.

1121
00:57:36.470 --> 00:57:37.500
And hope to joy

1122
00:57:37.500 --> 00:57:40.330
is little less in joy thanhope enjoyed.

1123
00:57:40.330 --> 00:57:43.130
By this the weary lords shallmake their way seem short,

1124
00:57:43.130 --> 00:57:45.470
as mine hath done by sightof what I have,

1125
00:57:45.470 --> 00:57:47.830
your noble company.

1126
00:57:47.830 --> 00:57:51.200
Of much less value is mycompany than your good words.

1127
00:57:52.400 --> 00:57:53.570
But who comes here?

1128
00:57:53.570 --> 00:57:55.330
It is my son, young HarryPercy,

1129
00:57:55.330 --> 00:57:56.830
sent from my brother,Worcester, whencesoever.

1130
00:57:56.830 --> 00:57:57.830
Harry.

1131
00:58:00.570 --> 00:58:03.030
How fares your uncle?

1132
00:58:03.030 --> 00:58:06.800
I had thought, my lord, to havelearned his health of you.

1133
00:58:06.800 --> 00:58:08.670
Why, is he not with thequeen?

1134
00:58:08.670 --> 00:58:10.430
No, my good lord.

1135
00:58:10.430 --> 00:58:13.400
He hath forsook the court,broken his staff of office,

1136
00:58:13.400 --> 00:58:15.230
and dispersed thehousehold of the king.

1137
00:58:15.230 --> 00:58:16.400
What was his reason?

1138
00:58:16.400 --> 00:58:18.330
He was not so resolvedwhen last we spaketogether.

1139
00:58:18.330 --> 00:58:22.970
Because your lordship wasproclaimed traitor.

1140
00:58:22.970 --> 00:58:25.130
But he, my lord, is goneto Ravenspurgh

1141
00:58:25.130 --> 00:58:27.330
to offer service to theduke of Hereford,

1142
00:58:27.330 --> 00:58:28.900
and sent me over byBerkeley

1143
00:58:28.900 --> 00:58:31.700
to discover what power theduke of York had levied there,

1144
00:58:31.700 --> 00:58:34.000
then with directions torepair to Ravenspurgh.

1145
00:58:34.000 --> 00:58:36.300
Have you forgot the dukeof Hereford, boy?

1146
00:58:37.870 --> 00:58:40.570
No, my good lord, for thatis not forgot

1147
00:58:40.570 --> 00:58:42.400
which ne'er I didremember.

1148
00:58:42.400 --> 00:58:43.400
To my knowledge,

1149
00:58:43.400 --> 00:58:45.230
I never in my life didlook on him.

1150
00:58:45.230 --> 00:58:47.500
Then learn to know himnow.

1151
00:58:47.500 --> 00:58:49.300
This is the duke.

1152
00:58:52.100 --> 00:58:53.270
My gracious lord,

1153
00:58:55.100 --> 00:58:57.170
I tender you my service,

1154
00:58:57.170 --> 00:59:01.770
such as it is, beingtender, raw, and young,

1155
00:59:01.770 --> 00:59:04.230
which elder days shallripen and confirm

1156
00:59:04.230 --> 00:59:07.270
to more approved serviceand desert.

1157
00:59:07.270 --> 00:59:09.900
I thank thee, gentlePercy,

1158
00:59:09.900 --> 00:59:12.830
and be sure I count myselfin nothing else so happy

1159
00:59:12.830 --> 00:59:16.200
as in a soul rememberingmy good friends.

1160
00:59:16.200 --> 00:59:18.970
And, as my fortune ripenswith thy love,

1161
00:59:18.970 --> 00:59:22.500
it shall be still thy truelove's recompense.

1162
00:59:22.500 --> 00:59:25.100
My heart this covenantmakes.

1163
00:59:25.100 --> 00:59:26.930
My hand thus seals it.

1164
00:59:27.930 --> 00:59:29.300
How far is it to Berkeley,

1165
00:59:29.300 --> 00:59:33.330
and what stir keeps goodold York there with hismen of war?

1166
00:59:33.330 --> 00:59:37.700
There stands the castle byyon tuft of trees,

1167
00:59:37.700 --> 00:59:40.530
manned with 300 men, as Ihave heard.

1168
00:59:40.530 --> 00:59:43.700
And in it are the lords ofYork, Berkeley, and Seymour.

1169
00:59:43.700 --> 00:59:46.170
None else of name andnoble estimate.

1170
00:59:46.170 --> 00:59:48.030
Here come the lords ofRoss and Willoughby,

1171
00:59:48.030 --> 00:59:51.330
bloody with spurring andfiery red with haste.

1172
00:59:51.330 --> 00:59:53.730
Welcome, my lords.

1173
00:59:53.730 --> 00:59:57.270
I wot your love pursues abanished traitor.

1174
00:59:57.270 --> 01:00:00.200
All my treasury is yet butunfelt thanks,

1175
01:00:00.200 --> 01:00:01.500
which more enriched

1176
01:00:01.500 --> 01:00:03.930
shall be your love andlabor's recompense.

1177
01:00:03.930 --> 01:00:06.300
Your presence makes usrich, most noble lord--

1178
01:00:06.300 --> 01:00:08.770
And far surmounts ourlabor to attain it.

1179
01:00:08.770 --> 01:00:12.070
Evermore thanks, theexchequer of the poor,

1180
01:00:12.070 --> 01:00:15.530
which, till my infantfortune comes to years,

1181
01:00:15.530 --> 01:00:17.870
stands for my bounty.

1182
01:00:17.870 --> 01:00:19.530
But who comes here?

1183
01:00:19.530 --> 01:00:21.870
It is my lord of Berkeley,as I guess.

1184
01:00:23.370 --> 01:00:25.930
My lord of Hereford, mymessage is to you.

1185
01:00:25.930 --> 01:00:29.470
My lord, my answer is toLancaster,

1186
01:00:29.470 --> 01:00:31.700
and I am come to seek thatname in England.

1187
01:00:31.700 --> 01:00:33.670
And I must find that titlein your tongue

1188
01:00:33.670 --> 01:00:35.800
before I make reply toaught you say.

1189
01:00:35.800 --> 01:00:37.600
Mistake me not, my lord.

1190
01:00:37.600 --> 01:00:41.630
'Tis not my meaning to razeone title of your honor out.

1191
01:00:41.630 --> 01:00:45.730
To you, my lord, I come,what lord you will,

1192
01:00:45.730 --> 01:00:47.670
from the most graciousregent of this land,

1193
01:00:47.670 --> 01:00:50.130
the duke of York, to knowwhat pricks you on

1194
01:00:50.130 --> 01:00:52.200
to take advantage of theabsent time

1195
01:00:52.200 --> 01:00:55.270
and fright our nativepeace with self-born arms.

1196
01:00:55.270 --> 01:00:58.270
I shall not need transportmy words by you.

1197
01:00:58.270 --> 01:01:00.100
Here comes His Grace inperson.

1198
01:01:02.130 --> 01:01:04.400
My noble uncle.

1199
01:01:04.400 --> 01:01:08.600
Show me thy humble heartand not thy knee,

1200
01:01:08.600 --> 01:01:11.070
whose duty is deceivableand false.

1201
01:01:11.070 --> 01:01:12.070
My gracious uncle--

1202
01:01:12.070 --> 01:01:13.070
Tut, tut.

1203
01:01:13.070 --> 01:01:15.270
Grace me no grace, noruncle me no uncle.

1204
01:01:15.270 --> 01:01:17.730
I am no traitor's uncle,

1205
01:01:17.730 --> 01:01:22.330
and that word "grace" inan ungracious mouth is butprofane.

1206
01:01:22.330 --> 01:01:24.770
Why have those banishedand forbidden legs

1207
01:01:24.770 --> 01:01:27.130
dared once to touch a dustof England's ground?

1208
01:01:27.130 --> 01:01:28.470
But then more "why."

1209
01:01:28.470 --> 01:01:30.130
Why have they dared tomarch

1210
01:01:30.130 --> 01:01:32.230
so many miles upon herpeaceful bosom,

1211
01:01:32.230 --> 01:01:34.730
frighting her pale facedvillages with war

1212
01:01:34.730 --> 01:01:38.000
and ostentation ofdespised arms?

1213
01:01:38.000 --> 01:01:42.630
Comest thou because theanointed king is hence?

1214
01:01:42.630 --> 01:01:45.600
Why, foolish boy, the kingis left behind,

1215
01:01:45.600 --> 01:01:48.170
and in my loyal bosom lieshis power.

1216
01:01:49.700 --> 01:01:52.130
Were I but now the lord ofsuch hot youth

1217
01:01:52.130 --> 01:01:54.530
as when brave Gaunt, thyfather, and myself

1218
01:01:54.530 --> 01:01:57.500
rescued the Black Prince,that young Mars of men,

1219
01:01:57.500 --> 01:01:59.730
from forth the ranks ofmany thousand French.

1220
01:01:59.730 --> 01:02:03.070
Oh, then how quickly wouldthis arm of mine,

1221
01:02:03.070 --> 01:02:05.270
now prisoner to the palsy,chastise thee

1222
01:02:05.270 --> 01:02:07.900
and minister correction tothy fault.

1223
01:02:07.900 --> 01:02:10.870
My gracious uncle, let meknow my fault.

1224
01:02:10.870 --> 01:02:13.370
On what condition standsit and wherein?

1225
01:02:13.370 --> 01:02:17.970
Even in condition of theworst degree,

1226
01:02:17.970 --> 01:02:20.670
in gross rebellion anddetested treason.

1227
01:02:20.670 --> 01:02:22.370
Thou art a banished man

1228
01:02:22.370 --> 01:02:25.270
and here art come beforethe expiration of thy time

1229
01:02:25.270 --> 01:02:28.730
in braving arms againstthy sovereign.

1230
01:02:28.730 --> 01:02:31.070
As I was banished, I wasbanished Hereford.

1231
01:02:31.070 --> 01:02:33.900
But as I come, I come forLancaster.

1232
01:02:35.570 --> 01:02:37.970
And, noble Uncle, Ibeseech Your Grace.

1233
01:02:37.970 --> 01:02:41.670
Look on my wrongs with anindifferent eye.

1234
01:02:41.670 --> 01:02:43.670
You are my father,

1235
01:02:43.670 --> 01:02:47.730
for methinks in you I seeold Gaunt alive.

1236
01:02:47.730 --> 01:02:49.770
Oh, then, my father, willyou permit

1237
01:02:49.770 --> 01:02:53.670
that I shall standcondemned a wanderingvagabond,

1238
01:02:53.670 --> 01:02:56.430
my rights and royaltiesplucked from my armsperforce

1239
01:02:56.430 --> 01:02:59.270
and given away to upstartunthrifts?

1240
01:02:59.270 --> 01:03:01.970
Wherefore was I born?

1241
01:03:01.970 --> 01:03:04.770
If that my cousin king beking in England,

1242
01:03:04.770 --> 01:03:08.100
it must be granted I amduke of Lancaster.

1243
01:03:08.100 --> 01:03:12.430
You have a son, Aumerle,my noble cousin.

1244
01:03:12.430 --> 01:03:15.330
Had you first died, and hebeen thus trod down,

1245
01:03:15.330 --> 01:03:17.870
he should have found hisuncle Gaunt a father

1246
01:03:17.870 --> 01:03:22.030
to rouse his wrongs andchase them to the bay.

1247
01:03:22.030 --> 01:03:24.470
I am denied to sue mylivery here,

1248
01:03:24.470 --> 01:03:27.230
and yet my letters patentsgive me leave.

1249
01:03:27.230 --> 01:03:29.870
My father's goods are alldistrained and sold,

1250
01:03:29.870 --> 01:03:33.070
and these and all are allamiss employed.

1251
01:03:33.070 --> 01:03:34.730
What would you have me do?

1252
01:03:37.530 --> 01:03:41.130
I am a subject, and Ichallenge law.

1253
01:03:41.130 --> 01:03:42.930
Attorneys are denied me,

1254
01:03:42.930 --> 01:03:45.400
and therefore, personallyI lay my claim

1255
01:03:45.400 --> 01:03:47.500
to my inheritance of freedescent.

1256
01:03:50.200 --> 01:03:52.870
The noble duke hath beentoo much abused.

1257
01:03:52.870 --> 01:03:54.900
It stands Your Grace uponto do him right.

1258
01:03:54.900 --> 01:03:57.170
Base men by his endowmentsare made great.

1259
01:03:57.170 --> 01:03:59.470
My lords of England, letme tell you this.

1260
01:03:59.470 --> 01:04:01.930
I have had feeling of mycousin's wrongs

1261
01:04:01.930 --> 01:04:03.400
and labored all I could todo him right.

1262
01:04:03.400 --> 01:04:06.370
But in this kind to come,in braving arms,

1263
01:04:06.370 --> 01:04:08.330
be his own carver and cutout his way

1264
01:04:08.330 --> 01:04:11.630
to find out right withwrong, it may not be.

1265
01:04:11.630 --> 01:04:13.300
And you who do abet him inthis kind

1266
01:04:13.300 --> 01:04:15.070
cherish rebellion and arerebels all.

1267
01:04:15.070 --> 01:04:20.070
The noble duke hath sworn hiscoming is but for his own.

1268
01:04:20.070 --> 01:04:21.270
And for the right of that,

1269
01:04:21.270 --> 01:04:24.400
we all have strongly swornto give him aid

1270
01:04:24.400 --> 01:04:27.970
and let him never see joythat breaks that oath.

1271
01:04:30.730 --> 01:04:32.270
Well, well.

1272
01:04:32.270 --> 01:04:35.170
I see the issue of thesearms.

1273
01:04:35.170 --> 01:04:37.070
I cannot mend it, I mustneeds confess,

1274
01:04:37.070 --> 01:04:39.830
because my power is weakand all ill left.

1275
01:04:39.830 --> 01:04:40.870
But if I could,

1276
01:04:40.870 --> 01:04:42.500
by Him that gave me life,

1277
01:04:42.500 --> 01:04:44.500
I would attach you all andmake you stoop

1278
01:04:44.500 --> 01:04:48.000
unto the sovereign mercyof the king.

1279
01:04:48.000 --> 01:04:53.670
But since I cannot, be itknown to you I do remainas neuter.

1280
01:04:56.000 --> 01:04:59.030
And so farewell...

1281
01:05:04.230 --> 01:05:07.400
unless you please to enterin the castle

1282
01:05:07.400 --> 01:05:09.930
and there repose you forthis night.

1283
01:05:09.930 --> 01:05:14.970
An offer, Uncle, that wewill accept.

1284
01:05:14.970 --> 01:05:18.800
But we must win Your Grace togo with us to Bristol Castle,

1285
01:05:18.800 --> 01:05:22.370
which they say is heldby Bushy, Bagot, andtheir complices,

1286
01:05:22.370 --> 01:05:23.930
the caterpillars of thecommonwealth,

1287
01:05:23.930 --> 01:05:26.670
which I have sworn to weedand pluck away.

1288
01:05:26.670 --> 01:05:27.930
It may be that I will gowith you.

1289
01:05:27.930 --> 01:05:29.800
No, but yet I'll pause,

1290
01:05:29.800 --> 01:05:32.800
for I am loath to breakour country's laws.

1291
01:05:32.800 --> 01:05:36.700
Nor friends nor foes, tome welcome you are.

1292
01:05:36.700 --> 01:05:39.930
Things past redress arenow with me past care.

1293
01:05:41.400 --> 01:05:44.100
My lord of Salisbury, wehave stayed ten days

1294
01:05:44.100 --> 01:05:45.930
and hardly kept ourcountrymen together,

1295
01:05:45.930 --> 01:05:48.430
and yet we hear no tidingsfrom the king.

1296
01:05:48.430 --> 01:05:50.070
Therefore we will disperseourselves.

1297
01:05:50.070 --> 01:05:51.070
Farewell.

1298
01:05:51.070 --> 01:05:52.930
Stay yet another day, thoutrusty Welshman.

1299
01:05:52.930 --> 01:05:56.030
The king reposeth all hisconfidence in thee.

1300
01:06:00.730 --> 01:06:01.900
'Tis thought the king isdead.

1301
01:06:01.900 --> 01:06:03.500
We will not stay.

1302
01:06:03.500 --> 01:06:06.100
The bay trees in ourcountry are all withered

1303
01:06:06.100 --> 01:06:09.130
and meteors fright thefixed stars of heaven.

1304
01:06:09.130 --> 01:06:11.170
The pale faced moon looksbloody on the earth,

1305
01:06:11.170 --> 01:06:14.930
and lean looked prophetswhisper fearful change.

1306
01:06:14.930 --> 01:06:18.430
Rich men look sad andruffians dance and leap,

1307
01:06:18.430 --> 01:06:20.970
the one in fear to losewhat they enjoy,

1308
01:06:20.970 --> 01:06:23.800
the other to enjoy by rageand war.

1309
01:06:23.800 --> 01:06:28.530
These signs forerun thedeath or fall of kings.

1310
01:06:28.530 --> 01:06:29.670
Farewell.

1311
01:06:29.670 --> 01:06:31.870
Our countrymen have goneand fled,

1312
01:06:31.870 --> 01:06:34.700
as well assured Richard,their king, is dead.

1313
01:06:39.630 --> 01:06:44.370
Bushy and Green, I willnot vex your souls--

1314
01:06:44.370 --> 01:06:47.170
since presently your soulsmust part your bodies--

1315
01:06:47.170 --> 01:06:50.230
with too much urging yourpernicious lives,

1316
01:06:50.230 --> 01:06:52.300
for it were no charity.

1317
01:06:52.300 --> 01:06:54.470
Yet to wash your bloodfrom off my hands,

1318
01:06:54.470 --> 01:06:55.930
here in the view of men

1319
01:06:55.930 --> 01:06:58.800
I will unfold some causesof your deaths.

1320
01:07:00.800 --> 01:07:04.800
You have misled a prince,a royal king,

1321
01:07:04.800 --> 01:07:07.530
a happy gentleman in bloodand lineaments,

1322
01:07:07.530 --> 01:07:11.630
by you unhappied anddisfigured clean.

1323
01:07:11.630 --> 01:07:14.430
You have in manner withyour sinful hours

1324
01:07:14.430 --> 01:07:17.130
made a divorce betwixt hisqueen and him,

1325
01:07:17.130 --> 01:07:19.130
broke the possession of aroyal bed,

1326
01:07:19.130 --> 01:07:22.330
and stained the beauty ofa fair queen's cheeks

1327
01:07:22.330 --> 01:07:28.300
with tears drawn from hereyes by your foul wrongs.

1328
01:07:28.300 --> 01:07:31.730
Myself, a prince byfortune of my birth,

1329
01:07:31.730 --> 01:07:33.470
near to the king inblood--

1330
01:07:33.470 --> 01:07:37.270
and near in love till you didmake him misinterpret me--

1331
01:07:37.270 --> 01:07:40.330
have stooped my neck underyour injuries

1332
01:07:40.330 --> 01:07:44.000
and sighed my Englishbreath in foreign clouds,

1333
01:07:44.000 --> 01:07:47.270
eating the bitter bread ofbanishment,

1334
01:07:47.270 --> 01:07:51.130
whilst you have fed uponmy signories,

1335
01:07:51.130 --> 01:07:54.930
disparked my parks andfelled my forest woods,

1336
01:07:54.930 --> 01:07:58.070
from my own windows tornmy household coat,

1337
01:07:58.070 --> 01:08:01.530
razed out my imprese,leaving me no sign,

1338
01:08:01.530 --> 01:08:04.700
save men's opinions and myliving blood,

1339
01:08:04.700 --> 01:08:07.330
to show the world I am agentleman.

1340
01:08:09.170 --> 01:08:13.400
This and much more, muchmore than twice all this,

1341
01:08:13.400 --> 01:08:16.200
condemns you to the death.

1342
01:08:16.200 --> 01:08:18.900
See them delivered over toexecution and the hand ofdeath.

1343
01:08:18.900 --> 01:08:20.970
More welcome is the strokeof death to me

1344
01:08:20.970 --> 01:08:22.700
than Bolingbroke toEngland.

1345
01:08:22.700 --> 01:08:24.270
Lords, farewell.

1346
01:08:24.270 --> 01:08:26.400
My comfort is that heavenwill take our souls

1347
01:08:26.400 --> 01:08:29.200
and plague injustice withthe pains of hell.

1348
01:08:29.200 --> 01:08:31.700
My Lord Northumberland,see them dispatched.

1349
01:08:38.000 --> 01:08:39.000
Uncle,

1350
01:08:40.630 --> 01:08:42.770
you say the queen is atyour house.

1351
01:08:43.870 --> 01:08:46.830
For God's sake, fairly lether be entreated.

1352
01:08:46.830 --> 01:08:49.930
Tell her I send to her mykind commends.

1353
01:08:49.930 --> 01:08:52.130
Take special care mygreetings be delivered.

1354
01:08:53.870 --> 01:08:55.970
A gentleman of mine I havedispatched

1355
01:08:55.970 --> 01:08:58.370
with letters of your loveto her at large.

1356
01:08:58.370 --> 01:08:59.800
Thanks, gentle Uncle.

1357
01:09:07.400 --> 01:09:08.830
Come, lords; away.

1358
01:09:08.830 --> 01:09:11.670
To fight with Glendowerand his complices:

1359
01:09:11.670 --> 01:09:14.830
awhile to work, and after,holiday.

1360
01:09:19.370 --> 01:09:21.470
Barkloughly Castle callthey this at hand?

1361
01:09:21.470 --> 01:09:22.470
Yea, my lord.

1362
01:09:23.500 --> 01:09:24.570
How brooks Your Grace theair

1363
01:09:24.570 --> 01:09:26.200
after your late tossing onthe breaking seas?

1364
01:09:26.200 --> 01:09:28.700
Needs must I like it well.

1365
01:09:28.700 --> 01:09:34.030
I weep for joy to standupon my kingdom once again.

1366
01:09:34.030 --> 01:09:35.930
Dear earth,

1367
01:09:35.930 --> 01:09:38.270
I do salute thee with myhands,

1368
01:09:38.270 --> 01:09:41.630
though rebels wound theewith their horses' hoofs.

1369
01:09:41.630 --> 01:09:44.070
As a long-parted motherwith her child

1370
01:09:44.070 --> 01:09:47.570
plays fondly with her tearsand smiles in meeting,

1371
01:09:47.570 --> 01:09:52.670
so weeping, smiling, greetI thee, my earth,

1372
01:09:52.670 --> 01:09:55.830
and do thee favors with myroyal hands.

1373
01:09:58.300 --> 01:10:01.230
Feed not thy sovereign'sfoe, my gentle earth,

1374
01:10:02.330 --> 01:10:06.370
nor with thy sweets comforthis ravenous sense,

1375
01:10:06.370 --> 01:10:09.900
but let thy spiders thatsuck up thy venom

1376
01:10:09.900 --> 01:10:13.570
and heavy-gaited toads liein their way,

1377
01:10:13.570 --> 01:10:15.870
doing annoyance to thetreacherous feet

1378
01:10:15.870 --> 01:10:20.200
which with usurping stepsdo trample thee.

1379
01:10:20.200 --> 01:10:23.730
Yield stinging nettles tomine enemies.

1380
01:10:23.730 --> 01:10:27.070
And when they from thybosom pluck a flower,

1381
01:10:27.070 --> 01:10:31.100
guard it, I pray thee,with a lurking adder

1382
01:10:31.100 --> 01:10:33.900
whose double-tongue maywith a mortal touch

1383
01:10:33.900 --> 01:10:36.730
throw death upon thysovereign's enemies.

1384
01:10:38.870 --> 01:10:42.670
Mock not my senselessconjuration, lords.

1385
01:10:42.670 --> 01:10:45.300
This earth shall have afeeling

1386
01:10:45.300 --> 01:10:48.200
and these stones provearmed soldiers

1387
01:10:48.200 --> 01:10:53.330
ere her native king shallfalter under foulrebellion's arms.

1388
01:10:53.330 --> 01:10:54.430
Fear not, my lord.

1389
01:10:54.430 --> 01:10:55.600
That power that made youking

1390
01:10:55.600 --> 01:10:58.100
hath power to keep youking in spite of all.

1391
01:10:58.100 --> 01:11:00.870
The means that heavenyields must be embraced

1392
01:11:00.870 --> 01:11:02.370
and not neglected,

1393
01:11:02.370 --> 01:11:06.070
else, if heaven would, andwe will not,

1394
01:11:06.070 --> 01:11:07.570
heaven's offer we refuse,

1395
01:11:07.570 --> 01:11:09.530
the proffered means ofsuccor and redress.

1396
01:11:09.530 --> 01:11:12.200
He means, my lord, that weare too remiss

1397
01:11:12.200 --> 01:11:13.770
whilst Bolingbroke,through our security,

1398
01:11:13.770 --> 01:11:16.170
grows strong and great insubstance and in power.

1399
01:11:16.170 --> 01:11:18.100
Discomfortable cousin.

1400
01:11:18.100 --> 01:11:20.330
Know'st thou not that whenthe searching eye of heaven

1401
01:11:20.330 --> 01:11:23.500
is hid behind the globe andlights the lower world,

1402
01:11:23.500 --> 01:11:26.100
then thieves and robbersrange abroad unseen

1403
01:11:26.100 --> 01:11:29.170
in murders and in outrage,boldly here.

1404
01:11:29.170 --> 01:11:31.870
But when from under thisterrestrial ball

1405
01:11:31.870 --> 01:11:35.100
he fires the proud tops ofthe eastern pines

1406
01:11:35.100 --> 01:11:37.900
and darts his lightthrough every guilty hole,

1407
01:11:37.900 --> 01:11:40.830
then murders, treasons,and detested sins,

1408
01:11:40.830 --> 01:11:43.630
the cloak of night beingplucked from off their backs,

1409
01:11:43.630 --> 01:11:47.830
stand bare and naked,trembling at themselves?

1410
01:11:47.830 --> 01:11:51.500
So when this thief, thistraitor, Bolingbroke,

1411
01:11:51.500 --> 01:11:54.670
who all this while hathreveled in the night

1412
01:11:54.670 --> 01:11:57.770
whilst we were wanderingwith the antipodes,

1413
01:11:57.770 --> 01:12:01.900
shall see us rising in ourthrone, the east.

1414
01:12:01.900 --> 01:12:05.370
His treasons will sitblushing on his face,

1415
01:12:05.370 --> 01:12:07.730
not able to endure thesight of day,

1416
01:12:07.730 --> 01:12:12.070
but self-affrightedtremble at his sin.

1417
01:12:12.070 --> 01:12:16.200
Not all the water in therough, rude sea

1418
01:12:16.200 --> 01:12:20.170
can wash the balm off froman anointed king.

1419
01:12:20.170 --> 01:12:23.800
The breath of worldly mencannot depose

1420
01:12:23.800 --> 01:12:26.500
the deputy elected by theLord.

1421
01:12:26.500 --> 01:12:28.870
For every man thatBolingbroke hath pressed

1422
01:12:28.870 --> 01:12:31.970
to lift shrewd steelagainst our golden crown,

1423
01:12:31.970 --> 01:12:37.670
God for his Richard hathin heavenly pay a gloriousangel.

1424
01:12:37.670 --> 01:12:40.230
Then, if angels fight,

1425
01:12:40.230 --> 01:12:42.830
weak men must fall,

1426
01:12:42.830 --> 01:12:46.600
for heaven still guardsthe right.

1427
01:12:46.600 --> 01:12:47.770
Welcome, my lord.

1428
01:12:47.770 --> 01:12:49.770
How far off lies yourpower?

1429
01:12:49.770 --> 01:12:52.100
Nor near nor farther off,my gracious lord,

1430
01:12:52.100 --> 01:12:54.130
than this weak arm.

1431
01:12:54.130 --> 01:12:55.700
Discomfort guides mytongue

1432
01:12:55.700 --> 01:12:58.400
and bids me speak ofnothing but despair.

1433
01:12:58.400 --> 01:13:01.530
One day too late, I fearme, gracious Lord,

1434
01:13:01.530 --> 01:13:03.800
hath clouded all thy happydays on earth.

1435
01:13:03.800 --> 01:13:05.470
Oh, call back yesterday.

1436
01:13:05.470 --> 01:13:06.700
Bid time return,

1437
01:13:06.700 --> 01:13:09.400
and thou shalt have 12,000fighting men.

1438
01:13:09.400 --> 01:13:12.930
Today, today-- unhappyday, too late--

1439
01:13:12.930 --> 01:13:18.470
o'erthrows thy joys, friends,fortune, and thy state.

1440
01:13:18.470 --> 01:13:21.730
For all the Welshmen,hearing thou wert dead,

1441
01:13:21.730 --> 01:13:25.130
are gone to Bolingbroke,dispersed and fled.

1442
01:13:27.500 --> 01:13:29.270
Comfort, my liege.

1443
01:13:29.270 --> 01:13:31.570
Why looks Your Grace sopale?

1444
01:13:31.570 --> 01:13:34.770
But now the blood of 20,000men did triumph in my face,

1445
01:13:34.770 --> 01:13:38.030
and they are fled.

1446
01:13:38.030 --> 01:13:41.070
And till so much bloodthither come again,

1447
01:13:41.070 --> 01:13:44.870
Have I not reason to lookpale and dead?

1448
01:13:44.870 --> 01:13:49.770
All souls that will besafe fly from my side,

1449
01:13:49.770 --> 01:13:53.000
for time hath set a blotupon my pride.

1450
01:13:53.000 --> 01:13:54.030
Comfort, my liege.

1451
01:13:54.030 --> 01:13:56.100
Remember who you are.

1452
01:13:57.600 --> 01:13:59.900
I had forgot myself.

1453
01:13:59.900 --> 01:14:01.270
Am I not king?

1454
01:14:02.730 --> 01:14:05.130
Awake, thou cowardmajesty.

1455
01:14:05.130 --> 01:14:06.430
Thou sleepest.

1456
01:14:06.430 --> 01:14:10.170
Is not the king's name20,000 names?

1457
01:14:10.170 --> 01:14:12.300
Arm, arm, my name.

1458
01:14:12.300 --> 01:14:16.200
A puny subject strikes atthy great glory.

1459
01:14:16.200 --> 01:14:19.770
Look not to the ground, yefavorites of a king.

1460
01:14:19.770 --> 01:14:21.200
Are we not high?

1461
01:14:21.200 --> 01:14:22.830
High be our thoughts.

1462
01:14:22.830 --> 01:14:26.570
I know my uncle York hathpower enough to serve ourturn.

1463
01:14:26.570 --> 01:14:27.770
But who comes here?

1464
01:14:30.770 --> 01:14:33.170
More health and happinessbetide my liege

1465
01:14:33.170 --> 01:14:35.630
than can my care-tunedtongue deliver him.

1466
01:14:37.030 --> 01:14:40.530
Mine ear is open and myheart prepared.

1467
01:14:40.530 --> 01:14:44.700
The worst is worldly lossthou canst unfold.

1468
01:14:44.700 --> 01:14:47.700
Say, is my kingdom lost?

1469
01:14:47.700 --> 01:14:50.100
Why, 'twas my care.

1470
01:14:50.100 --> 01:14:53.430
And what loss is it to berid of care?

1471
01:14:53.430 --> 01:14:55.870
Strives Bolingbroke to beas great as we?

1472
01:14:55.870 --> 01:14:57.870
Greater he shall not be.

1473
01:14:57.870 --> 01:14:59.170
If he serve God,

1474
01:14:59.170 --> 01:15:02.500
we'll serve Him, too, andbe His fellow so.

1475
01:15:02.500 --> 01:15:04.670
Revolt our subjects?

1476
01:15:04.670 --> 01:15:06.800
That we cannot mend.

1477
01:15:06.800 --> 01:15:09.900
They break their faith toGod as well as us.

1478
01:15:09.900 --> 01:15:15.830
Cry woe, destruction,ruin, and decay.

1479
01:15:15.830 --> 01:15:20.730
The worst is death, anddeath will have his day.

1480
01:15:20.730 --> 01:15:22.270
Glad am I that YourHighness

1481
01:15:22.270 --> 01:15:25.130
is so armed to bear thetidings of calamity.

1482
01:15:28.100 --> 01:15:30.370
Like an unseasonablestormy day

1483
01:15:30.370 --> 01:15:33.500
which makes the silverrivers drown their shores,

1484
01:15:33.500 --> 01:15:36.700
as if the world were alldissolved to tears,

1485
01:15:36.700 --> 01:15:40.730
so high above his limitsswells the rage ofBolingbroke,

1486
01:15:40.730 --> 01:15:42.370
covering your fearful land

1487
01:15:42.370 --> 01:15:45.400
with hard, bright steel andhearts harder than steel.

1488
01:15:48.170 --> 01:15:50.770
Whitebeards have armed theirthin and hairless scalps

1489
01:15:50.770 --> 01:15:52.300
against thy majesty.

1490
01:15:52.300 --> 01:15:56.030
Boys with women's voicesstrive to speak big

1491
01:15:56.030 --> 01:15:57.470
and clap their femalejoints

1492
01:15:57.470 --> 01:16:00.700
in stiff, unwieldy armsagainst thy crown.

1493
01:16:00.700 --> 01:16:02.630
Thy very beadsmen learn tobend their bows

1494
01:16:02.630 --> 01:16:05.000
of double-fatal yewagainst thy state.

1495
01:16:05.000 --> 01:16:09.900
Yea, distaff women managerusty bills against thy seat.

1496
01:16:09.900 --> 01:16:12.530
Both young and old rebel,

1497
01:16:12.530 --> 01:16:15.370
and all goes worse than Ihave power to tell.

1498
01:16:16.930 --> 01:16:22.800
Too well, too well thoutell'st a tale so ill.

1499
01:16:28.770 --> 01:16:31.070
Where is the earl ofWiltshire?

1500
01:16:31.070 --> 01:16:33.130
Where is Bagot?

1501
01:16:33.130 --> 01:16:35.330
What is become of Bushy?

1502
01:16:35.330 --> 01:16:37.200
Where is Green,

1503
01:16:37.200 --> 01:16:38.500
that they have let thedangerous enemy

1504
01:16:38.500 --> 01:16:42.370
measure our confines withsuch peaceful steps?

1505
01:16:42.370 --> 01:16:45.570
If we prevail, their headsshall pay for it.

1506
01:16:45.570 --> 01:16:48.000
I warrant they have madepeace with Bolingbroke.

1507
01:16:48.000 --> 01:16:50.170
Peace have they made withhim indeed, my lord.

1508
01:16:50.170 --> 01:16:52.400
Oh, villains!

1509
01:16:52.400 --> 01:16:56.530
Vipers damned withoutredemption!

1510
01:16:56.530 --> 01:17:00.230
Dogs easily won to fawn onany man.

1511
01:17:00.230 --> 01:17:05.200
Snakes, in my heart bloodwarmed, that sting my heart.

1512
01:17:05.200 --> 01:17:08.770
Three Judases, each onethrice worse than Judas.

1513
01:17:08.770 --> 01:17:10.700
Would they make peace?

1514
01:17:10.700 --> 01:17:11.900
Terrible hell make war

1515
01:17:11.900 --> 01:17:15.070
upon their spotted soulsfor this offence.

1516
01:17:15.070 --> 01:17:17.330
Sweet love, I see changinghis property

1517
01:17:17.330 --> 01:17:19.830
turns to the sourest andmost deadly hate.

1518
01:17:21.870 --> 01:17:24.000
Again uncurse their souls.

1519
01:17:24.000 --> 01:17:27.870
Their peace is made withheads and not with hands.

1520
01:17:27.870 --> 01:17:28.970
Those whom you curse

1521
01:17:28.970 --> 01:17:31.800
have felt the worst ofdeath's destroying wound

1522
01:17:31.800 --> 01:17:36.830
and lie full low, gravedin the hollow ground.

1523
01:17:46.100 --> 01:17:48.830
Is Bushy, Green, and theearl of Wiltshire dead?

1524
01:17:48.830 --> 01:17:52.330
Aye, all of them atBristol lost their heads.

1525
01:17:54.670 --> 01:17:56.270
Where is the duke, myfather, with his power?

