Doubly divorced.

2287
02:06:07.070 --> 02:06:10.430
Bad men, you violate atwofold marriage,

2288
02:06:10.430 --> 02:06:12.200
'twixt my crown and me,

2289
02:06:12.200 --> 02:06:15.670
and then betwixt me and mymarried wife.

2290
02:06:15.670 --> 02:06:18.830
Let me unkiss the oath'twixt thee and me.

2291
02:06:21.470 --> 02:06:28.300
And yet not so, for with akiss 'twas made.

2292
02:06:28.300 --> 02:06:30.870
Part us, Northumberland--

2293
02:06:30.870 --> 02:06:32.200
I toward the north,

2294
02:06:32.200 --> 02:06:35.730
where shivering cold andsickness pines the clime.

2295
02:06:35.730 --> 02:06:37.030
My wife to France,

2296
02:06:37.030 --> 02:06:40.570
from whence, set forth inpomp,

2297
02:06:40.570 --> 02:06:44.570
she came adorned hitherlike sweet May,

2298
02:06:44.570 --> 02:06:47.830
sent back like Hallowmasor short'st of day.

2299
02:06:47.830 --> 02:06:48.830
And must we be divided?

2300
02:06:48.830 --> 02:06:49.930
Must we part?

2301
02:06:49.930 --> 02:06:57.930
Aye, hand from hand, mylove, and heart from heart.

2302
02:06:57.930 --> 02:07:00.670
Banish us both and sendthe king with me.

2303
02:07:00.670 --> 02:07:03.130
That were some love butlittle policy.

2304
02:07:03.130 --> 02:07:05.400
Then whither he goes,thither let me go.

2305
02:07:05.400 --> 02:07:09.230
So two, together weeping,make one woe.

2306
02:07:09.230 --> 02:07:12.800
Weep thou for me inFrance, I for thee here.

2307
02:07:12.800 --> 02:07:16.600
Better far off than near,be ne'er the near.

2308
02:07:16.600 --> 02:07:19.530
Go, count thy way withsighs.

2309
02:07:19.530 --> 02:07:21.670
I mine with groans.

2310
02:07:21.670 --> 02:07:27.430
So longest way shall havethe longest moans.

2311
02:07:27.430 --> 02:07:31.830
Twice for one step I'llgroan, the way being short,

2312
02:07:31.830 --> 02:07:34.830
and piece the way out witha heavy heart.

2313
02:07:34.830 --> 02:07:37.870
Come, come, in wooingsorrow let's be brief,

2314
02:07:37.870 --> 02:07:40.400
since, wedding it, thereis such length in grief.

2315
02:07:40.400 --> 02:07:44.530
One kiss shall stop ourmouths, and dumbly part.

2316
02:07:49.170 --> 02:07:51.900
Thus give I mine, and thustake I thy heart.

2317
02:07:51.900 --> 02:07:53.770
Give me mine own again.

2318
02:07:53.770 --> 02:07:58.130
'Twere no good part totake on me to keep andkill thy heart.

2319
02:08:06.500 --> 02:08:08.670
Now I have mine own again.

2320
02:08:08.670 --> 02:08:13.470
Be gone that I may striveto kill it with a groan.

2321
02:08:18.230 --> 02:08:22.470
We make woe wanton withthis fond delay.

2322
02:08:22.470 --> 02:08:25.200
Once more, adieu.

2323
02:08:25.200 --> 02:08:27.130
The rest let sorrow say.

2324
02:08:33.270 --> 02:08:34.470
My lord,

2325
02:08:36.400 --> 02:08:39.070
you told me you would tellthe rest,

2326
02:08:39.070 --> 02:08:41.670
when weeping made youbreak the story off,

2327
02:08:41.670 --> 02:08:44.730
of our two cousins cominginto London.

2328
02:08:44.730 --> 02:08:45.730
Where did I leave?

2329
02:08:45.730 --> 02:08:49.070
At that sad stop, my lord,

2330
02:08:49.070 --> 02:08:52.430
where rude, misgovernedhands from windows' tops

2331
02:08:52.430 --> 02:08:57.570
threw dust and rubbish onKing Richard's head.

2332
02:08:57.570 --> 02:09:00.930
Then, as I said, the duke,great Bolingbroke,

2333
02:09:00.930 --> 02:09:03.570
mounted upon a hot andfiery steed,

2334
02:09:03.570 --> 02:09:06.330
which his aspiring riderseemed to know,

2335
02:09:06.330 --> 02:09:09.100
with slow but stately pacekept on his course,

2336
02:09:09.100 --> 02:09:13.130
whilst all tongues cried "Godsave thee, Bolingbroke."

2337
02:09:14.770 --> 02:09:16.570
You would have thought thevery windows spake,

2338
02:09:16.570 --> 02:09:19.170
so many greedy looks ofyoung and old

2339
02:09:19.170 --> 02:09:21.400
through casements dartedtheir desiring eyes

2340
02:09:21.400 --> 02:09:22.730
upon his visage,

2341
02:09:22.730 --> 02:09:24.970
and that all the wallswith painted imagery

2342
02:09:24.970 --> 02:09:26.970
had said at once "Jesupreserve thee.

2343
02:09:26.970 --> 02:09:29.870
Welcome, Bolingbroke."

2344
02:09:29.870 --> 02:09:33.130
Whilst he, from the oneside to the other turning,

2345
02:09:33.130 --> 02:09:34.630
bareheaded,

2346
02:09:34.630 --> 02:09:37.230
lower than his proudsteed's neck,

2347
02:09:37.230 --> 02:09:39.070
bespake them thus:

2348
02:09:39.070 --> 02:09:41.030
"I thank thee,countrymen."

2349
02:09:42.400 --> 02:09:44.570
And thus still doing, thushe passed along.

2350
02:09:44.570 --> 02:09:48.570
Alack, poor Richard.

2351
02:09:48.570 --> 02:09:50.570
Where rode he the whilst?

2352
02:09:51.530 --> 02:09:54.170
As in a theatre, the eyesof men,

2353
02:09:54.170 --> 02:09:56.900
after a well-graced actorleaves the stage,

2354
02:09:56.900 --> 02:09:59.170
are idly bent on him thatenters next,

2355
02:09:59.170 --> 02:10:01.870
thinking his prattle to betedious.

2356
02:10:01.870 --> 02:10:05.230
Even so, but with muchmore contempt,

2357
02:10:05.230 --> 02:10:08.170
did men's eyes scowl ongentle Richard.

2358
02:10:08.170 --> 02:10:09.970
No man cried, "God savehim."

2359
02:10:09.970 --> 02:10:12.900
No joyful tongue gave himhis welcome home.

2360
02:10:15.970 --> 02:10:21.370
But dust was thrown uponhis sacred head,

2361
02:10:23.900 --> 02:10:27.970
which with such gentlesorrow he shook off,

2362
02:10:27.970 --> 02:10:32.300
his face still combatingwith tears and smiles,

2363
02:10:32.300 --> 02:10:36.570
the badges of his griefand patience,

2364
02:10:36.570 --> 02:10:38.770
that had not God, for somestrong purpose,

2365
02:10:38.770 --> 02:10:41.030
steeled the hearts of men,they must perforce havemelted,

2366
02:10:41.030 --> 02:10:44.500
and barbarism itself havepitied him.

2367
02:10:44.500 --> 02:10:46.300
But heaven hath a hand inthese events,

2368
02:10:46.300 --> 02:10:49.570
to whose high will webound our calm contents.

2369
02:10:52.370 --> 02:10:55.130
To Bolingbroke we aresworn subjects now,

2370
02:10:55.130 --> 02:10:57.270
whose state and honor Ifor aye allow.

2371
02:10:59.670 --> 02:11:01.670
Here comes my son Aumerle.

2372
02:11:01.670 --> 02:11:02.900
Aumerle that was.

2373
02:11:02.900 --> 02:11:04.630
But that is lost for beingRichard's friend.

2374
02:11:04.630 --> 02:11:07.470
And, madam, you must callhim Rutland now.

2375
02:11:07.470 --> 02:11:10.130
I am in parliament pledgefor his truth

2376
02:11:10.130 --> 02:11:13.100
and lasting fealty to thenew made king.

2377
02:11:13.100 --> 02:11:14.570
Welcome, my son.

2378
02:11:16.770 --> 02:11:19.300
Who are the violets now

2379
02:11:19.300 --> 02:11:23.330
that strew the green lapof the new come spring?

2380
02:11:23.330 --> 02:11:26.670
Madam, I know not, nor Igreatly care not.

2381
02:11:26.670 --> 02:11:28.230
God knows I had as lief benone as one.

2382
02:11:28.230 --> 02:11:30.770
Well, bear you well inthis new spring of time,

2383
02:11:30.770 --> 02:11:33.400
lest you be cropped beforeyou come to prime.

2384
02:11:36.300 --> 02:11:38.100
What news from Oxford?

2385
02:11:38.100 --> 02:11:40.200
Those jousts and triumphshold?

2386
02:11:40.200 --> 02:11:41.670
For aught I know, my lord,they do.

2387
02:11:41.670 --> 02:11:43.970
You will be there, I know.

2388
02:11:43.970 --> 02:11:45.530
If God prevent not, Ipurpose so.

2389
02:11:45.530 --> 02:11:47.800
What seal is that, thathangs without thy bosom?

2390
02:11:49.470 --> 02:11:52.630
Yea, look'st thou pale?

2391
02:11:52.630 --> 02:11:54.030
Let me see the writing.

2392
02:11:54.030 --> 02:11:55.930
My lord, 'tis nothing.

2393
02:11:55.930 --> 02:11:58.770
No matter, then, who seeit.

2394
02:11:58.770 --> 02:12:00.330
I will be satisfied.

2395
02:12:00.330 --> 02:12:01.930
Let me see the writing.

2396
02:12:04.270 --> 02:12:05.400
I do beseech Your Grace topardon me.

2397
02:12:05.400 --> 02:12:07.930
It is a matter of smallconsequence,

2398
02:12:07.930 --> 02:12:09.800
which for some reasons Iwould not have seen.

2399
02:12:09.800 --> 02:12:14.770
Which for some reasons,sir, I mean to see.

2400
02:12:14.770 --> 02:12:17.800
I fear--I fear--

2401
02:12:17.800 --> 02:12:19.400
What should you fear?

2402
02:12:19.400 --> 02:12:22.330
'Tis nothing but some bond

2403
02:12:22.330 --> 02:12:25.530
that he is entered intofor gay apparel againstthe triumph day.

2404
02:12:25.530 --> 02:12:26.600
Bound to himself.

2405
02:12:26.600 --> 02:12:28.970
What doth he with a bondthat he is bound to?

2406
02:12:28.970 --> 02:12:29.970
Wife, thou art a fool.

2407
02:12:29.970 --> 02:12:33.570
Boy, boy, let me see thewriting.

2408
02:12:33.570 --> 02:12:35.070
I do beseech you, pardonme.

2409
02:12:35.070 --> 02:12:36.100
I may not show it.

2410
02:12:36.100 --> 02:12:37.370
I will be satisfied.

2411
02:12:37.370 --> 02:12:38.400
Let me see it, I say.

2412
02:12:47.370 --> 02:12:49.730
Treason.

2413
02:12:49.730 --> 02:12:51.070
Foul treason.

2414
02:12:53.100 --> 02:12:54.900
Villain.

2415
02:12:54.900 --> 02:12:56.230
Traitor.

2416
02:12:56.230 --> 02:12:57.370
Slave.

2417
02:12:57.370 --> 02:12:58.370
My lord, what is thematter?

2418
02:12:58.370 --> 02:12:59.370
Ho.

2419
02:12:59.370 --> 02:13:00.670
Who is within there?

2420
02:13:00.670 --> 02:13:02.100
Saddle my horse.

2421
02:13:02.100 --> 02:13:04.330
God for his mercy, whattreachery is here.

2422
02:13:04.330 --> 02:13:05.400
Why, what is it, my lord?

2423
02:13:05.400 --> 02:13:07.530
Bring me my boots, I say.

2424
02:13:07.530 --> 02:13:09.270
Saddle my horse.

2425
02:13:09.270 --> 02:13:12.670
Now, upon mine honor, bymy life, my troth,

2426
02:13:12.670 --> 02:13:14.300
I will appeach thevillain.

2427
02:13:14.300 --> 02:13:15.300
What is the matter?

2428
02:13:15.300 --> 02:13:16.300
Peace, foolish woman.

2429
02:13:16.300 --> 02:13:17.970
I will not peace.

2430
02:13:17.970 --> 02:13:19.070
What is the matter,Aumerle?

2431
02:13:19.070 --> 02:13:20.370
Good Mother, be content.

2432
02:13:20.370 --> 02:13:22.970
It is no more than my poorlife must answer.

2433
02:13:22.970 --> 02:13:24.400
Thy life answer.

2434
02:13:24.400 --> 02:13:26.800
Bring me my boots.

2435
02:13:26.800 --> 02:13:28.470
I will unto the king.

2436
02:13:28.470 --> 02:13:29.470
Strike him, Aumerle.

2437
02:13:29.470 --> 02:13:31.500
Poor boy, thou art amazed.

2438
02:13:31.500 --> 02:13:33.430
Hence, villain.

2439
02:13:33.430 --> 02:13:35.170
Never more come in mysight.

2440
02:13:35.170 --> 02:13:36.170
Give me my boots, I say.

2441
02:13:36.170 --> 02:13:38.000
Why, York, what wilt thoudo?

2442
02:13:38.000 --> 02:13:42.000
Wilt thou not hide thetrespass of thine own?

2443
02:13:42.000 --> 02:13:44.970
Have we more sons or arewe like to have?

2444
02:13:44.970 --> 02:13:48.330
Is not my teeming datedrunk up with time?

2445
02:13:48.330 --> 02:13:50.930
And wilt thou pluck myfair son from mine age

2446
02:13:50.930 --> 02:13:53.870
and rob me of a happymother's name?

2447
02:13:53.870 --> 02:13:55.170
Is he not like thee?

2448
02:13:55.170 --> 02:13:56.700
Is he not thine own?

2449
02:13:56.700 --> 02:13:58.200
Thou fond, mad woman,

2450
02:13:58.200 --> 02:14:01.300
wilt thou conceal thisdark conspiracy?

2451
02:14:01.300 --> 02:14:03.870
A dozen of them here haveta'en the sacrament

2452
02:14:03.870 --> 02:14:05.830
and interchangeably setdown their hands

2453
02:14:05.830 --> 02:14:08.000
to kill the king atOxford.

2454
02:14:09.930 --> 02:14:12.070
He shall be none.

2455
02:14:12.070 --> 02:14:13.070
We will keep him here.

2456
02:14:13.070 --> 02:14:14.770
Then what is that to him?

2457
02:14:14.770 --> 02:14:16.230
Away, fond woman.

2458
02:14:16.230 --> 02:14:20.070
Were he 20 times my son, Iwould appeach him.

2459
02:14:20.070 --> 02:14:23.230
Hadst thou groaned for himas I have done,

2460
02:14:23.230 --> 02:14:25.530
thou wouldst be morepitiful.

2461
02:14:25.530 --> 02:14:28.200
But now I know thy mind.

2462
02:14:28.200 --> 02:14:31.100
Thou dost suspect that I havebeen disloyal to thy bed

2463
02:14:31.100 --> 02:14:34.370
and that he is a bastard,not thy son.

2464
02:14:34.370 --> 02:14:37.770
Sweet York, sweet husband,be not of that mind.

2465
02:14:37.770 --> 02:14:39.070
He is as like thee as aman may be,

2466
02:14:39.070 --> 02:14:42.600
not like to me, or any ofmy kin, and yet I love him.

2467
02:14:42.600 --> 02:14:44.430
Make way, unruly woman.

2468
02:14:44.430 --> 02:14:46.170
After, Aumerle.

2469
02:14:46.170 --> 02:14:48.030
Mount thee upon his horse.

2470
02:14:48.030 --> 02:14:50.970
Spur post and get beforehim to the king.

2471
02:14:50.970 --> 02:14:52.700
I'll not be long behind.

2472
02:14:52.700 --> 02:14:56.530
Though I be old, I doubt notbut to ride as fast as York.

2473
02:14:56.530 --> 02:15:00.430
And never will I rise upfrom the ground

2474
02:15:00.430 --> 02:15:03.100
till Bolingbroke havepardoned thee.

2475
02:15:03.100 --> 02:15:04.130
Away.

2476
02:15:04.130 --> 02:15:05.170
Be gone.

2477
02:15:10.330 --> 02:15:14.200
What means our cousin that hestares and looks so wildly?

2478
02:15:14.200 --> 02:15:16.800
God save Your Grace.

2479
02:15:16.800 --> 02:15:18.300
I do beseech Your Majesty

2480
02:15:18.300 --> 02:15:20.270
to have some conferencewith Your Grace alone.

2481
02:15:22.430 --> 02:15:24.270
Withdraw yourselves andleave us here alone.

2482
02:15:24.270 --> 02:15:25.330
My lord!

2483
02:15:35.800 --> 02:15:38.400
What is the matter withour cousin now?

2484
02:15:40.630 --> 02:15:43.230
Forever may my knees growto the earth,

2485
02:15:43.230 --> 02:15:45.200
my tongue cleave to myroof within my mouth

2486
02:15:45.200 --> 02:15:48.000
unless a pardon ere I riseor speak.

2487
02:15:48.000 --> 02:15:51.100
Intended or committed wasthis fault?

2488
02:15:51.100 --> 02:15:53.400
If on the first, howheinous e'er it be

2489
02:15:53.400 --> 02:15:55.900
to win thy after love Ipardon thee.

2490
02:15:58.770 --> 02:16:00.270
Then give me leave that Imay turn the key

2491
02:16:00.270 --> 02:16:03.270
that no man enter till mytale be done.

2492
02:16:03.270 --> 02:16:04.270
Have thy desire.

2493
02:16:09.000 --> 02:16:10.630
My liege, look to thyself.

2494
02:16:10.630 --> 02:16:11.670
Beware.

2495
02:16:11.670 --> 02:16:14.530
Thou hast a traitor in thypresence there.

2496
02:16:14.530 --> 02:16:17.900
Villain, I'll make theesafe.

2497
02:16:17.900 --> 02:16:19.670
Stay thy revengeful hand.

2498
02:16:19.670 --> 02:16:21.370
Thou hast not cause tofear.

2499
02:16:21.370 --> 02:16:23.370
Open the door, or I willbreak it open.

2500
02:16:27.400 --> 02:16:29.470
What is the matter?

2501
02:16:29.470 --> 02:16:30.500
Uncle, speak.

2502
02:16:30.500 --> 02:16:31.870
Recover breath.

2503
02:16:31.870 --> 02:16:35.330
Tell us how near is dangerthat we may arm us toencounter it.

2504
02:16:35.330 --> 02:16:36.630
Peruse this writing

2505
02:16:36.630 --> 02:16:40.330
and thou shalt know thetreason that my hasteforbids me show.

2506
02:16:40.330 --> 02:16:42.370
Remember as thou read'stthy promise passed.

2507
02:16:43.300 --> 02:16:45.500
I do repent me.

2508
02:16:45.500 --> 02:16:46.630
Read not my name there.

2509
02:16:46.630 --> 02:16:49.970
My heart is notconfederate with my hand.

2510
02:16:49.970 --> 02:16:53.500
It was, villain, ere thyhand did set it down.

2511
02:16:53.500 --> 02:16:55.970
I tore it from thetraitor's bosom, king.

2512
02:16:55.970 --> 02:16:59.700
Fear, and not love, begetshis penitence.

2513
02:16:59.700 --> 02:17:02.000
Forget to pity him, lestthy pity prove

2514
02:17:02.000 --> 02:17:04.600
a serpent that will stingthee to the heart.

2515
02:17:04.600 --> 02:17:10.500
Oh, heinous, strong, andbold conspiracy.

2516
02:17:10.500 --> 02:17:14.070
Oh, loyal father of atreacherous son,

2517
02:17:14.070 --> 02:17:17.200
thou sheer, immaculate,and silver fountain

2518
02:17:17.200 --> 02:17:20.230
from whence this streamthrough muddy passages

2519
02:17:20.230 --> 02:17:22.570
hath held his current anddefiled himself,

2520
02:17:22.570 --> 02:17:26.630
thy overflow of goodconverts to bad,

2521
02:17:26.630 --> 02:17:29.530
and thy abundant goodnessshall excuse

2522
02:17:29.530 --> 02:17:32.270
this deadly blot in thydigressing son.

2523
02:17:32.270 --> 02:17:35.900
So shall my virtue be hisvice's bawd.

2524
02:17:35.900 --> 02:17:38.000
And he shall spend minehonor with his shame

2525
02:17:38.000 --> 02:17:41.170
as thriftless sons theirscraping fathers' gold.

2526
02:17:41.170 --> 02:17:44.330
Mine honor lives when hisdishonor dies,

2527
02:17:44.330 --> 02:17:47.270
or my shamed life in hisdishonor lies.

2528
02:17:47.270 --> 02:17:50.930
Thou kill'st me in hislife, giving him breath.

2529
02:17:50.930 --> 02:17:51.930
The traitor lives.

2530
02:17:51.930 --> 02:17:54.130
The true man's put todeath.

2531
02:17:54.130 --> 02:17:56.830
What ho, my liege.

2532
02:17:56.830 --> 02:18:00.100
For God's sake, let me in.

2533
02:18:00.100 --> 02:18:03.200
What shrill-voiced suppliantmakes this eager cry?

2534
02:18:03.200 --> 02:18:06.630
A woman, and thy aunt,great king.

2535
02:18:06.630 --> 02:18:07.930
'Tis I.

2536
02:18:07.930 --> 02:18:10.070
Speak with me.

2537
02:18:10.070 --> 02:18:11.200
Pity me.

2538
02:18:11.200 --> 02:18:13.070
Open the door.

2539
02:18:13.070 --> 02:18:17.530
A beggar begs that neverbegged before.

2540
02:18:17.530 --> 02:18:19.630
Our scene is altered froma serious thing

2541
02:18:19.630 --> 02:18:21.900
